{"title_page": "71st New York Infantry", "text_new": "{{Lead too short|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=71st Infantry Regiment\n| image=71 Inf Rgt COA.png\n| image_size = 120\n|caption=Coat of arms\n|country={{USA}}\n|allegiance=\n|type=Infantry\n|branch=[[New York Army National Guard]]\n|dates=1850\u2013present\n|specialization=\n|command_structure=\n|size=Battalion\n|current_commander=\n|garrison=New York City\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|nickname=\"The American Guard\"\n|motto=\"''Pro aris et pro focis''\"\n|colors=\n|march=''The Gallant Seventy-First''\n|mascot=\n|battles=[[American Civil War]]\n* [[First Bull Run]]\n* [[Battle of Gettysburg]]\n[[Spanish\u2013American War]]\n* [[Battle of San Juan Hill]]\n* [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican Border]]\n[[World War I]]<br />\n[[World War II]]\n* [[Attu Island]]\n* [[Ardennes Offensive]]\n|notable_commanders=\n|anniversaries=\n}}\n{{US Regiments\n|previous=[[70th Infantry Regiment (United States)|70th Infantry Regiment]]\n|next=[[74th Infantry Regiment (United States)|74th Infantry Regiment]]\n}}\n[[File:71st New York State Militia at Washington Navy Yard 34786v.jpg|thumb|In Washington during the Civil War]]\n[[File:Infantry camp. 71st. N.Y. Inf. at Camp Douglas, 1861 - NARA - 524509 (cropped).jpg|thumb|NCO and enlisted men of the 71st]]\nThe '''71st Infantry Regiment''' is an organization of the [[New York State Guard]]. Formerly, the 71st Infantry was a regiment of the New York State Militia and then the Army National Guard from 1850 to 1993. The regiment was not renumbered during the 1918 national reorganization due to being broken up to staff other units from 1917\u20131919,<ref name=Sut1>Sutliffe, pp. 1-4, 34-39</ref> and never received a National Guard number.\n\n==History==\nIn the fall of 1849, the Order of United Americans, related to the [[Know Nothing Party]], held a meeting to organize a \"distinctively American regiment.\"<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1894/04/01/archives/seventyfirsts-new-home-the-regiment-takes-possession-of-its-armory.html \"Seventy-First's New Home\"]. (April 1, 1894). ''The New York Times''.</ref>\n\nThe 71st New York was formed on October 23, 1850, and was called \"The American Rifles\" and later \"The American Guard.\"<ref name=\"veteran\">{{cite web|url=http://www.suvcw.org/ny/camps/ellis/71st.htm|title=71st|website=www.suvcw.org}}</ref> Originally, the founders, J.M. Parker, [[Hamilton Fish|Hamilton W. Fish, Sr]], Hamilton W. Fish, Jr. and William Kellock, had political links to the [[Know-Nothing Party]]. Initially there were six companies recruited. One officer in A Company, Captain Parker, resigned after hearing a \"foreigner\" paraded with the \"American Rifles.\"<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\nIn Spring 1852, the American Rifles had eight companies, enough to be enrolled as a regiment of the state militia, and were assigned the regimental number of 71st. Its first commander was Colonel Abraham S. Vosburgh, previously its quartermaster. Vosburgh would remain commanding officer until his death on May 20, 1861. Henry P. Martin, previously adjutant, became lieutenant colonel in 1854. He would remain with the 71st through the first years of the Civil War. Its arsenal was located at Seventh Avenue and 35th Street.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\nThe regiment became the \"American Guard\" in 1853 when their Ogden long rifles were replaced with muskets, which could carry bayonets. These, in turn, were replaced with Minie rifles in 1857.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\nOn July 4, 1857, the regiment, along with the seventh New York, served as riot control personnel during the riots in the Sixth Ward between the [[Dead Rabbits]] and the Bowery Boys. During this action, Dead Rabbit leader Mickey Free was killed and the regiment captured an 8-lb howitzer from the rioters. The regiment was called into action again during the [[Bayley Seton Hospital#History|quarantine riot]] of September 1858 in Staten Island.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\"/><ref name=\"DNMA\">{{cite web|url=http://dmna.ny.gov/historic/reghist/spanAm/infantry/71stInf/71stInfMain.htm|title=71st Regiment Infantry, New York Volunteers during the Spanish\u2013American War \u2013 NY Military Museum and Veterans Research Center|website=dmna.ny.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn 1858, the \"Light Guard,\" New York's oldest military unit, detached from the 55th New York and became A Company. This led to some tension, because the \"Light Guard\" had several \"foreigners\" in the ranks.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n===American Civil War===\n\n[[File:Private Eli F. Bruce of Co. E, 71st New York Infantry Regiment in uniform with sword) - Bogardus, photographer, 363 Broadway, cor. Franklin St., New York LCCN2017659610.jpg|thumb|right|Private Eli F. Bruce of Co. E, 71st New York Infantry Regiment. From the  Liljenquist Family Collection of Civil War Photographs, Prints and Photographs Division, [[Library of Congress]]]]\n\nOn April 16, 1861, 380 men mustered under Colonel Vosburgh at the State Arsenal, in response to President Lincoln's call for 75,000 troops. On April 21, the 71st paraded down Broadway and headed to the front.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n====Arrival in Washington====\nThe 71st, then called to service for three months under Colonel Henry P. Martin, arrived in Washington on May 21, 1861, and was bivouacked at the [[Washington Navy Yard]]. While the army assembled, a team made up of members of the regiment defeated the Washington Nationals baseball club by a score of 41 to 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impactprospects.com/bghistory.htm|title=\"Civil War Baseball: Baseball and the Blue and the Gray,\"  accessed 1-15-2008|access-date=2008-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106075459/http://www.impactprospects.com/bghistory.htm|archive-date=2008-01-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe regiment took part in the occupation of [[Alexandria, Virginia]], in May 1861, accompanying the New York Fire Zouaves and Colonel Ephraim E. Ellsworth, who was killed in the action.\n\nA detachment of the 71st, with two howitzers, fought at Acquia Creek and Port Tobacco in May and June 1861. Private Charles B. Hall was the first man injured on any U.S. vessel in the war.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n====First Battle of Bull Run====\nThe 71st New York State Volunteer Infantry was organized in the Second Brigade (Colonel [[Ambrose Everett Burnside]]) of the Second Division (Colonel [[David Hunter]]).<ref>[http://www.pathsofthecivilwar.com/Pastfinder/PCWsummaryALL.asp?state=all&locationID=VA005 Paths of the Civil War<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715051914/http://www.pathsofthecivilwar.com/Pastfinder/PCWsummaryALL.asp?state=all&locationID=VA005 |date=July 15, 2011 }}</ref> On July 21, 1861, the 71st Infantry, under Colonel Martin's command, took part in the First Battle of Bull Run. Archaeological research on the battlefield at Manassas shows the 71st, along with the 1st and 2nd Rhode Island Infantry, faced the [[Louisiana Tigers|Tiger Rifles]] of Major Chatham Wheat's Louisiana Battalion, the only known unit engaged in fighting outfitted with .54-caliber muskets. The 71st supported the advance of the 2nd Rhode Island against Wheat's battalion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sha.org/|title=Society for Historical Archaeology|website=Society for Historical Archaeology}}</ref> The Illustrated London News noted \"The militia stood firm, firing and loading as if it were on parade.\"<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\nColonel Burnside's after-action report of July 24, 1861, noted:<blockquote>It was nearly 4 o'clock p.m. . . . when I was ordered to protect the retreat. The Seventy-first Regiment New York State Militia was formed between the retreating columns and the enemy by Colonel Martin, and the Second Regiment Rhode Island Volunteers by Lieutenant-Colonel Wheaton.</blockquote>\n\nHis follow-up after-action report added, \"I beg to again mention the bravery and steadiness manifested by Colonel Martin and his entire regiment, Seventy-first, both-on the field and during the retreat.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civilwarhome.com/burnside1stmanassas.htm|title=Col. Ambrose E. Burnside's OR For 1st Manassas (Bull Run)|website=www.civilwarhome.com}}</ref>\n\nCasualties included 62 officers and men.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\"/> The regiment was mustered out of service in New York on July 20, 1861. It was remustered on May 28, 1862, under Colonel Martin, and returned to the man the defenses of Washington in 1862.\n\n====Chancellorsville====\nColonel Henry K. Potter commanded the 71st New York State Volunteers (distinct from the 71st NYSNG), which was placed in the Second \"Excelsior\" Brigade (Brig. Gen. Joseph W. Revere) of the Second Division (Maj. Gen. Hiram G. Berry) of the Third Corps (Sickles) in the [[Battle of Chancellorsville]] in May 1863.\n\n====Gettysburg====\nThe 71st passed through [[Chambersburg, Pennsylvania]], on June 23, 1863,<ref>\u201cRachel Cormany Diary.\u201d {{cite web|url=http://etext.virginia.edu/etcbin/browse-valley?id%3DFD1006%26images%3Dimages%2Fmodeng%2FF%26data%3D%2Ftexts%2Fenglish%2Fcivilwar%2Fdiaries%26tag%3Dpublic |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-01-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050407162315/http://etext.virginia.edu/etcbin/browse-valley?id=FD1006&images=images%2Fmodeng%2FF&data=%2Ftexts%2Fenglish%2Fcivilwar%2Fdiaries&tag=public |archivedate=2005-04-07 }}</ref> it is often confused with the 71st New York Volunteers, an entirely separate, three year volunteer regiment, which fought at the [[Battle of Gettysburg]], as part of Sickle's III Corps, again in the Second \"Excelsior\" Brigade (Colonel [[William R. Brewster]]). The 71st militia served in the defense of Harrisburg during the battle of Gettysburg.\n\n====Return to New York====\nAfter the battle, the 71st was recalled to New York City to help suppress the 1863 draft riots (the militia unit that was mobilized to defend Harrisburg, not the volunteer unit that was involved with the actual battle at Gettysburg). The regiment was mustered out of service in 1864. Many members of the 71st joined the 124th New York, which carried on the name \"The American Guard.\" and took part in the Petersburg campaign. Others joined other regiments.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n===State duty===\nThe 71st also served to control the Orange riots of 1871, the railroad riots of July 1877, the switchmen's strike in Buffalo of August 1892, and the motorman's strike of 1895 in [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"DNMA\" />\n\nIn 1884, under accusations of financial mismanagement by Colonel Vose, 15 company-grade officers resigned. Colonel Vose blamed the problems on the Veterans Association.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1884/02/15/106142734.pdf |accessdate=January 15, 2008 |work=The New York Times |title=Laying The Blame On Col. Vose.; Fifteen Line Officers Of The Seventy-First Regiment Resign |date=February 15, 1884}}</ref>\n\nIn 1894, the 71st, under the command of Colonel Francis Vinton Greene, moved into its armory at 33rd and Park Avenue.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n===Spanish\u2013American War===\nIn the [[Spanish\u2013American War]], the 71st Regiment, New York Volunteers, were the first of twelve New York State regiments called to active service on May 10, 1898.<ref name=\"DNMA\" /> The regiment entrained to [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] on May 13, arriving on May 17. A week of confusion and quartermaster incompetence delayed their shipment to Cuba. The 71st was bivouacked along with the 1st U.S. Volunteer Cavalry, the \"Rough Riders\", in Tampa, who then stole a march on the 71st to steal their transport on the ''Tampa.'' The 71st's sea trip took two weeks<ref name=\"DNMA\"/> The confusion of this organization was cited as one of the reasons for the 1903 reforms of the Army and National Guard.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nThere were ten companies of the regiment, with 1,000 soldiers, organized into three battalions.\n\nArriving at Siboney, Cuba, on June 23, the 71st was brigaded with two regular regiments, the 6th and 16th Infantry Regiments in the First Brigade under Regular Army Brigadier General [[Hamilton S. Hawkins]], as part of General [[Jacob Ford Kent]]'s division, as part of the Fifth Corps under General Shafter. Although the 71st was regarded as one of the best National Guard regiments, it was equipped with obsolescent black powder rifles, and its commanding officer, Lieutenant Colonel Wallace A. Downs, reported that one-third of his men had never fired a rifle before.<ref name=millis>Millis, Walter. ''The Martial Spirit''. 1931, Ayer Publishing. p. 285. Accessed through Google Books.</ref>\n\nThe 71st was ordered to support the Rough Riders in a skirmish against Siboney's garrison, but the fighting was over before the New Yorkers could arrive. On June 27, the brigade moved towards Santiago, making slow progress over poor roads in the heat.<ref name=\"DNMA\" /> A letter from a private in the 71st noted \"Yesterday the line of march up the hill was strewn with blankets and extra clothing, even some of the 'regs' [U.S. Regulars] discarded clothes and walked in underwear.\"<ref name=Website>{{cite web |title=Private Oscar Hochstadter  of the 71st New York Volunteer Infantry Writes Home |url=http://www.spanamwar.com/71stNYletterhochstadter.html|publisher=The Spanish American War Centennial Website |accessdate=2012-11-02}}</ref>\n\n====The Battle of Santiago====\nThe regiment took part in the Battle of Santiago ([[Battle of San Juan Hill]]), though it did not take part in the attack. By now many members of the regiment were ill with malaria.<ref>Bates, William Graves (Colonel). \"A Summary of the History of the 71st Infantry, N.G.N.Y.\" In {{cite book|title=Seventy-first New York in the world war|url=https://archive.org/details/seventyfirstnew00sutlgoog|accessdate=2 November 2012|year=1922|publisher=J. J. Little & Ives|page=[https://archive.org/details/seventyfirstnew00sutlgoog/page/n580 516]}}</ref> The road on which Kent's First Brigade moved forked just before coming out of forested areas, and Kent ordered the 71st to take the left-hand road to join the 6th and 16th's left flank. As the regiment left the forest, the 71st was pinned down by accurate Spanish rifle fire from the heights of San Juan hill, preventing any advance.<ref name=\"millis\" />{{rp|285}}\n\nGeneral Hawkins wrote later that General Kent had the 71st detached from his brigade without his knowledge and contrary to his plans and intentions. His command post was two miles (3&nbsp;km) away and through a thick jungle of cactus.<ref name=\"times1900\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1900/01/29/archives/vindicates-71st-regiment-gen-hawkins-contradicts-the-testimony-of.html |work=The New York Times |title=VINDICATES 71ST REGIMENT; Gen. Hawkins Contradicts the Testimony of Gen. Kent. NO NOTICE OF CHANGED PLANS Says Trouble at San Juan Was Due to Men Being Taken Out of His Brigade Without His Knowledge |date=January 29, 1900}}</ref>\n\nSeveral commentators, including Lieutenant Colonel Philip Reade, Inspector General for General Kent, made disparaging remarks about the 71st's apparent lack of courage (though the malaria and heat were contributing factors). The official report of the 13th Infantry, leading Kent's Second Brigade, noted<blockquote>The men of the 71st were lying flat on the ground along the underbrush bordering the road with their feet toward the middle of the road... From the remarks they made to us all along the line as we passed them at a run, I inferred that they were in this prostrate formation for the purpose of avoiding exposure to bullets.<ref name=millis />{{rp|286}}</blockquote>\n\nThe regiment's commander, Lt. Colonel Downs, testified at a court of inquiry in 1899 that he had received no orders to advance since 10 a.m. and therefore held his men in reserve. He said the attack by Lawton's brigade on the right had been delayed, and Downs' last orders had been to wait until Lawton's attack was successful before moving forward. Colonel Reade<ref name=\"times1900\"/>  testified that he had to \"shove\" the 71st into the fight, though Company F commander Captain Malcolm Rafferty and 3rd Battalion commander Major Frank Keck responded immediately. Other men of the regiment also moved forward to join the regulars in the attack,<ref name=\"times1899\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1899/01/15/archives/71st-regiment-inquiry-several-witnesses-testify-in-favor-of-lieut.html |work=The New York Times |title=71ST REGIMENT INQUIRY; Several Witnesses Testify in Favor of Lieut. Col. Smith. TESTIMONY OF ONE EXPUNGED Lieut. Col. Reade's Report on the Conduct of the Command at Santiago Forwarded |date=January 15, 1899}}</ref> but historian Walter Millis noted that \"although the regiment as a whole soon recovered its morale, it had earned a black mark which the censorious publics who hadn't been there could not afterward forgive.\"<ref name=\"millis\" />{{rp|285}} Ironically, the first American soldier to reach the crest of San Juan Hill was Lieutenant Herbert Hyde True of Company L of the 71st (in Keck's battalion).<ref>True, Herbert Hyde. \"Sanguinary San Juan Hill.\" pp 121-122 in Buel, James William. ''Hero Tales of the American Soldier and Sailor as Told by the Heroes'' 1899, A. Holloway. Original from Harvard University Digitized October 16, 2007</ref>\n\n[[image:71st Infantry Regiment at NY Camp Wikoff in 1898.ogv|thumb|left|71st Infantry marching at [[Theodore Roosevelt County Park#Camp Wikoff|Camp Wikoff]], Long Island, NY, after returning from Cuba, September 1898. The picture shows many of the companies reduced to seven or eight men, and the whole regiment, rank and file is in a sad condition.]]\nThe Spanish garrison of Santiago surrendered on July 14, 1898. The 71st began to suffer many men sick from [[yellow fever]] and other tropical diseases. One lieutenant noted there were reports the regiment would be moved to Montauk Point, Long Island, to recuperate from the climate,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/12/weekinreview/word-for-word-letters-home-the-myriad-ways-in-which-war-has-been-hell.html |work=The New York Times |first=Joyce |last=Jensen |title=Word for Word/Letters Home; The Myriad Ways in Which War Has Been Hell |date=November 12, 2000}}</ref> and many men from the 71st were sent there to recover on the hospital ship ''Shinnecock''.<ref>\"More Sick from Montauk\" ''New York Times'', September 17, 1898{{full citation needed|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n\nUpon its return to New York State on August 22, the regiment could only muster 350 of its initial 1,000 men. Eighty men had been killed in the fighting around Santiago. The majority of the regiment was on sick leave or in the hospital. In October the 71st returned to Camp Black and on November 14, 1898, the regiment was mustered out.<ref name=\"DNMA\"/>\n\nFollowing the war, a board of inquiry was held at the 22nd Regiment on the conduct of the senior officers of the regiment, including Lieutenant Colonel Clinton H. Smith, the First Battalion commander. The testimony of witnesses was favorable to Lt. Col. Smith, noting he was present on the battlefield.<ref name=\"times1899\"/> However, Colonel Downs and Major John Whittle resigned their commissions. Two more officers were reprimanded. The board was reviewed by then Governor [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who noted \"the greater part of the Seventy-First of their own free will took part in the storming of San Juan hill, and showed that no matter how cowardly their officers might be, they were willing to obey their country's call.\"<ref>Harrison, W.B. ''Great Round World and what is Going on in it.''vol 10 (1899), pp 737\u2013738</ref>\n\nDespite the bad impression the regiment made as a whole in Santiago, many individual soldiers in the regiment were recognized for courage, including Corporal Lewis Benedict of Co. K (also in Keck's battalion), who \"received a commission as lieutenant in the regular service.\" Major Keck received a commission as a captain in the Regular Army and served in the Philippines.<ref>[http://www.phigam.org/history/Lists/spamwar.htm Phi Gamma Delta in the Spanish American War] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221014347/http://www.phigam.org/history/Lists/spamwar.htm |date= February 21, 2008 }}, accessed 1-15-2008</ref> After the war, Keck became prominent in New York City's social and business life. Another member of the 71st was Charles Johnson Post, who painted memorable watercolor paintings of the 71st in the 1898 war.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0FMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=24+USS+Maine+Burials&cd=8#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=LIFE|date=7 July 1958|publisher=Time Inc|via=Google Books|title = A Little War With A Big Result |pages = }}</ref>\n\n===The new armory===\nThe original armory of the regiment burned down in 1902. A new armory was built on the spot in 1905 by the firm of [[Clinton and Russell]], and was noted for its particularly fine exterior architecture.<ref>[http://www.andrewcusack.com/blog/2007/01/ Andrew Cusack] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104040320/http://www.andrewcusack.com/blog/2007/01/ |date=January 4, 2008 }}. Retrieved 01-16-2008.</ref> This armory was used not only for military training, but many public events such as annual stamp shows.\n\n===World War I===\nIn 1916, before the U.S. entry into [[World War I]], the 71st was mobilized as part of the U.S. Army force serving on the Mexican border.  The 71st mustered in on June 26, 1916, at New York City and mustered out at New York City on October 6, 1916.<ref>New York Mexican Punitive Campaign Muster Rolls for National Guard{{full citation needed|date=January 2020}}</ref> On March 25, 1917 the regiment was federalized,<ref>Sutliffe, p. 7</ref> but in August was required to provide 350 men to the [[69th Infantry Regiment (United States)|69th New York Infantry Regiment]], which was soon to fight overseas as the 165th Infantry Regiment.<ref>Sutliffe, p. 21</ref> On September 30, 1917, the 71st paraded down Fifth Avenue; however, the next day the regiment was \"skeletonized\" to provide cadre for other units, and was denied the opportunity to fight as a unit.<ref>Sutliffe, pp. 29-39</ref> Several of the officers and 1,375 enlisted men of the regiment were transferred to the [[105th Infantry Regiment (United States)|105th Infantry]], with the remainder were transferred to other elements of the [[27th Infantry Division (United States)|27th Division]] and other units.<ref>\"Lieut. H.H. Street Wounded; Served on Mexican Border with Old 71st\", ''New York Times'', August 14, 1918.</ref><ref name=Sut1/> After serving overseas with that division and other units, the 71st regiment's soldiers returned to New York in May 1919 and the unit was re-formed in the New York National Guard.<ref>\"Dozen Ships on Way With More Troops.\" ''New York Times'', May 27, 1919</ref>\n\nMen of the 71st served in Belgium and France during WWI with units of the 27th Division;<ref>Sutliffe, p. 522</ref> Joseph M. Cahill was in G Company (presumably of the 105th Infantry) and his military record lists the following battles: Hindenburg Line, John Oder Mer Ridge, La Salle River, and the following engagements: The Knoll, Gillimont Farm, Quennemont Farm, St. Maurice River, Viertaat Ridge, and finally the following Minor Actions East: Poperinohe Line and Dickebusch Sector.\n\nA partial listing of awards and commendations appears in Robert S. Sutliffe's ''Seventy-First New York in the World War'' (which can be seen on Google Books), it includes 11 US Army [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]es, 137 divisional citations, as well as 8 British decorations, 7 French decorations, 4 Belgium decorations, and Montenegrin Decorations.<ref>Sutliffe, pp. 367-401</ref>\n\n===Between the World Wars===\nFrom 1921-41, the 71st was brigaded with the 174th Infantry Regiment as part of the [[87th Infantry Brigade (United States) |87th Infantry Brigade]], [[44th Infantry Division (United States)|44th Infantry Division]].<ref>{{cite book|first = John J. |last = McGrath|title = The Brigade: A History|page =171|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KWrLJj-iTlAC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA171| publisher = DIANE Publishing |date = 2004|isbn =9781428910225}}</ref> It performed a number of civil and ceremonial duties. Its annual training was usually at [[Camp Smith (New York)|Camp Smith]] in [[Peekskill, New York]]. Its regimental armory served as a homeless shelter in 1934.<ref>\"Armory Is Opened To Homeless Men 71st And Two Others Will Be Used As Day-Time Shelter.\" ''New York Times'', December 18, 1934</ref> The 1940 and 1941 annual training took place at Fort Dix, New Jersey.\n\n===World War II===\nIn World War II, the 71st, consisting of three battalions, was part of the [[44th Infantry Division (United States)|44th Infantry Division]], which assembled at [[Fort Lewis, Washington]]. Headquarters Company of the 1st Battalion was detached to take part in the [[Battle of Attu|retaking of Attu Island]] in the [[Aleutian campaign]].  The 102d Engr Bn (CBT) also had its Company C serving in the Pacific Campaign.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nSergeant [[Charles A. MacGillivary]] of the 71st received the [[Medal of Honor]] for actions during the German Ardennes offensive of December 1944 near Woelfling, France, near the German border. On January 1, 1944, Sergeant MacGillivary was serving as company commander because of casualties among the officers. Ammunition was low and the company was pinned down. MacGillivary set out on his own to destroy the German machine guns menacing his company. He carried a sub-machine gun and grenades; when his submachine gun ran out of ammunition, he picked up a discarded weapon and continued the attack. MacGillivary wiped out the German positions and killed or wounded all of the defenders, at the cost of his left arm.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/06/30/us/c-a-macgillivary-83-dies-won-medal-of-honor.html |work=The New York Times |first=Richard |last=Goldstein |title=C. A. MacGillivary, 83, Dies; Won Medal of Honor |date=June 30, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn this offensive, the 71st encountered the [[17th SS Panzergrenadier Division G\u00f6tz von Berlichingen]], holding off eight attacks.\n\nThe Second Battalion and I Company of the Third Battatlion were both awarded [[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Presidential Unit Citation]]s.\n\nIn the last days of the war, the First Battalion crossed the Austrian border through a mountain pass and attacked a German division.\n\n===After World War II===\nThe 71st was not called to active duty in either the Korean War or the Vietnam War. It was called to state active duty in April 1979 to serve as prison guards at Taconic and [[Bedford Hills Correctional Facility for Women|Bedford Hills prison]]s during a correctional officers' strike.\n\nThe regiment's original armory was located at Park Avenue and 34th Street in Manhattan. It later moved to 125 West 14th Street.\n\nIn 1984, the Governor of New York, [[Mario Cuomo]], proposed disbanding the 71st and 106th Infantry to use their armory spaces for civilian purposes. The 71st Infantry Veterans' Association sued the state in court, stating that such realignment would violate state affirmative action guidelines since the 71st Infantry was predominantly black. The 71st received a favorable ruling.<ref>\"Court Order Rescues Historic Guard Unit,\" ''New York Times'', February 2, 1984</ref>\n\nOn August 31, 1993, the 71st disbanded as a National Guard unit.<ref name=\"veteran\"/> A detachment of the battalion in Batavia, New York, was kept on active duty.<ref>\"136 Guardsmen to stay active despite units' status\", ''Buffalo News'', February 12, 1993</ref> The First Battalion became a [[State Guard]] unit, serving with the 14th Infantry Brigade.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/09/AR2006080900262_pf.html |accessdate=January 14, 2008|title=U.S. Forces Repel Raid on Afghan Base |last=Garwood|first=Paul |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Symbols and traditions==\nThe regimental nickname is \"The American Guard.\" The regimental motto is \"Pro aris et pro focis,\" which can be translated \"For our homes and our families\" but see '[[Pro aris et focis]]'. The regimental march is \"The Gallant Seventy-First.\"\n\nThe regimental crest is a blue shield, edged in gold, charged with gold fasces with the ax head pointing to the left, supported by two gold crescents. (This is the opposite direction from the Italian fascist symbol.)<ref>[http://dmna.ny.gov/historic/heraldry/arngdui/71stInfantry.htm Heraldry: 71st Infantry]. New York State Military Museum. Retrieved July 31, 2013</ref>\n\nThe commanding officer of the regiment traditionally wore as his ceremonial sidearm a Colt revolver that was originally Colonel Martin's sidearm. This pistol was left with the senior officer of the regiment (or later, battalion) in the commanding officer's absence.\n\n==Commanding officers==\nDates in parentheses are known dates, but not start or ending dates.\n* Colonel Abram S. Vosburgh, 1852\u20131861\n* Colonel Henry P. Martin, 1861\u20131862\n* Colonel Charles H. Smith, 1862\u20131863\n* Colonel H.L. Trafford, 1863\u20131866\n* Colonel Theodore W. Parmalee, 1866\u20131869\n* Colonel Henry Rockafeller, 1869\u20131871\n* Colonel Richard Vose, 1871\u20131884\n* Colonel [[Edwin A. McAlpin]], 1885\n* Colonel Frederick Kopper, 1891\n* Colonel [[Francis Vinton Greene]], 1891\n* Colonel Johnathan T. Camp (1895)\n* Lieutenant Colonel Wallace A. Downs (1898)\u20131899\n* Colonel Walter Delamater (1936)\n\n==See also==\n* [[71st Infantry Regiment (United States)]]\n* [[Spanish American War Monument to the 71st Infantry Regiment]]\n* [[Joyce's 71st New York Regiment March]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Post, Charles Johnson. ''The Little War of Private Post: The Spanish\u2013American War Seen Up Close''. 1999, University of Nebraska Press. 352 pages. {{ISBN|0-8032-8757-7}}\n* Lieutenant Colonel Thomas Rafferty, Personal Recollections of the War of the Rebellion, Titled \"Gettysburg\" pages 1\u201332.\n* {{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/seventyfirstnewy00sutl|title=Seventy-first New York in the world war|first=Robert Stewart|last=Sutliffe|date=22 March 2018|publisher=New York, Printed by J. J. Little & Ives co.|via=Internet Archive}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the United States in the Spanish\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:United States Army regiments in World War II]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Civil War regiments|Infantry 071]]\n[[Category:Excelsior Brigade]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:State defense forces of the United States|New York, 71st Infantry Regiment]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:1850 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1850]]\n", "text_old": "{{Lead too short|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=71st Infantry Regiment\n| image=71 Inf Rgt COA.png\n| image_size = 120\n|caption=Coat of arms\n|country={{USA}}\n|allegiance=\n|type=Infantry\n|branch=[[New York Army National Guard]]\n|dates=1850\u2013present\n|specialization=\n|command_structure=\n|size=Battalion\n|current_commander=\n|garrison=New York City\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|nickname=\"The American Guard\"\n|motto=\"''Pro aris et pro focis''\"\n|colors=\n|march=''The Gallant Seventy-First''\n|mascot=\n|battles=[[American Civil War]]\n* [[First Bull Run]]\n* [[Battle of Gettysburg]]\n[[Spanish\u2013American War]]\n* [[Battle of San Juan Hill]]\n* [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican Border]]\n[[World War I]]<br />\n[[World War II]]\n* [[Attu Island]]\n* [[Ardennes Offensive]]\n|notable_commanders=\n|anniversaries=\n}}\n{{US Regiments\n|previous=[[70th Infantry Regiment (United States)|70th Infantry Regiment]]\n|next=[[74th Infantry Regiment (United States)|74th Infantry Regiment]]\n}}\n[[File:71st New York State Militia at Washington Navy Yard 34786v.jpg|thumb|In Washington during the Civil War]]\n[[File:Infantry camp. 71st. N.Y. Inf. at Camp Douglas, 1861 - NARA - 524509 (cropped).jpg|thumb|NCO and enlisted men of the 71st]]\nThe '''71st Infantry Regiment''' is an organization of the [[New York State Guard]]. Formerly, the 71st Infantry was a regiment of the New York State Militia and then the Army National Guard from 1850 to 1993. The regiment was not renumbered during the 1918 national reorganization due to being broken up to staff other units from 1917\u20131919,<ref name=Sut1>Sutliffe, pp. 1-4, 34-39</ref> and never received a National Guard number.\n\n==History==\nIn the fall of 1849, the Order of United Americans, related to the [[Know Nothing Party]], held a meeting to organize a \"distinctively American regiment.\"<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1894/04/01/archives/seventyfirsts-new-home-the-regiment-takes-possession-of-its-armory.html \"Seventy-First's New Home\"]. (April 1, 1894). ''The New York Times''.</ref>\n\nThe 71st New York was formed on October 23, 1850, and was called \"The American Rifles\" and later \"The American Guard.\"<ref name=\"veteran\">{{cite web|url=http://www.suvcw.org/ny/camps/ellis/71st.htm|title=71st|website=www.suvcw.org}}</ref> Originally, the founders, J.M. Parker, [[Hamilton Fish|Hamilton W. Fish, Sr]], Hamilton W. Fish, Jr. and William Kellock, had political links to the [[Know-Nothing Party]]. Initially there were six companies recruited. One officer in A Company, Captain Parker, resigned after hearing a \"foreigner\" paraded with the \"American Rifles.\"<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\nIn Spring 1852, the American Rifles had eight companies, enough to be enrolled as a regiment of the state militia, and were assigned the regimental number of 71st. Its first commander was Colonel Abraham S. Vosburgh, previously its quartermaster. Vosburgh would remain commanding officer until his death on May 20, 1861. Henry P. Martin, previously adjutant, became lieutenant colonel in 1854. He would remain with the 71st through the first years of the Civil War. Its arsenal was located at Seventh Avenue and 35th Street.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\nThe regiment became the \"American Guard\" in 1853 when their Ogden long rifles were replaced with muskets, which could carry bayonets. These, in turn, were replaced with Minie rifles in 1857.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\nOn July 4, 1857, the regiment, along with the seventh New York, served as riot control personnel during the riots in the Sixth Ward between the [[Dead Rabbits]] and the Bowery Boys. During this action, Dead Rabbit leader Mickey Free was killed and the regiment captured an 8-lb howitzer from the rioters. The regiment was called into action again during the [[Bayley Seton Hospital#History|quarantine riot]] of September 1858 in Staten Island.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\"/><ref name=\"DNMA\">{{cite web|url=http://dmna.ny.gov/historic/reghist/spanAm/infantry/71stInf/71stInfMain.htm|title=71st Regiment Infantry, New York Volunteers during the Spanish\u2013American War \u2013 NY Military Museum and Veterans Research Center|website=dmna.ny.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn 1858, the \"Light Guard,\" New York's oldest military unit, detached from the 55th New York and became A Company. This led to some tension, because the \"Light Guard\" had several \"foreigners\" in the ranks.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n===American Civil War===\n\n[[File:Private Eli F. Bruce of Co. E, 71st New York Infantry Regiment in uniform with sword) - Bogardus, photographer, 363 Broadway, cor. Franklin St., New York LCCN2017659610.jpg|thumb|right|Private Eli F. Bruce of Co. E, 71st New York Infantry Regiment. From the  Liljenquist Family Collection of Civil War Photographs, Prints and Photographs Division, [[Library of Congress]]]]\n\nOn April 16, 1861, 380 men mustered under Colonel Vosburgh at the State Arsenal, in response to President Lincoln's call for 75,000 troops. On April 21, the 71st paraded down Broadway and headed to the front.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n====Arrival in Washington====\nThe 71st, then called to service for three months under Colonel Henry P. Martin, arrived in Washington on May 21, 1861, and was bivouacked at the [[Washington Navy Yard]]. While the army assembled, a team made up of members of the regiment defeated the Washington Nationals baseball club by a score of 41 to 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impactprospects.com/bghistory.htm|title=\"Civil War Baseball: Baseball and the Blue and the Gray,\"  accessed 1-15-2008|access-date=2008-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106075459/http://www.impactprospects.com/bghistory.htm|archive-date=2008-01-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe regiment took part in the occupation of [[Alexandria, Virginia]], in May 1861, accompanying the New York Fire Zouaves and Colonel Ephraim E. Ellsworth, who was killed in the action.\n\nA detachment of the 71st, with two howitzers, fought at Acquia Creek and Port Tobacco in May and June 1861. Private Charles B. Hall was the first man injured on any U.S. vessel in the war.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n====First Battle of Bull Run====\nThe 71st New York State Volunteer Infantry was organized in the Second Brigade (Colonel [[Ambrose Everett Burnside]]) of the Second Division (Colonel [[David Hunter]]).<ref>[http://www.pathsofthecivilwar.com/Pastfinder/PCWsummaryALL.asp?state=all&locationID=VA005 Paths of the Civil War<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715051914/http://www.pathsofthecivilwar.com/Pastfinder/PCWsummaryALL.asp?state=all&locationID=VA005 |date=July 15, 2011 }}</ref> On July 21, 1861, the 71st Infantry, under Colonel Martin's command, took part in the First Battle of Bull Run. Archaeological research on the battlefield at Manassas shows the 71st, along with the 1st and 2nd Rhode Island Infantry, faced the [[Louisiana Tigers|Tiger Rifles]] of Major Chatham Wheat's Louisiana Battalion, the only known unit engaged in fighting outfitted with .54-caliber muskets. The 71st supported the advance of the 2nd Rhode Island against Wheat's battalion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sha.org/|title=Society for Historical Archaeology|website=Society for Historical Archaeology}}</ref> The Illustrated London News noted \"The militia stood firm, firing and loading as if it were on parade.\" <ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\nColonel Burnside's after-action report of July 24, 1861, noted:<blockquote>It was nearly 4 o'clock p.m. . . . when I was ordered to protect the retreat. The Seventy-first Regiment New York State Militia was formed between the retreating columns and the enemy by Colonel Martin, and the Second Regiment Rhode Island Volunteers by Lieutenant-Colonel Wheaton.</blockquote>\n\nHis follow-up after-action report added, \"I beg to again mention the bravery and steadiness manifested by Colonel Martin and his entire regiment, Seventy-first, both-on the field and during the retreat.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civilwarhome.com/burnside1stmanassas.htm|title=Col. Ambrose E. Burnside's OR For 1st Manassas (Bull Run)|website=www.civilwarhome.com}}</ref>\n\nCasualties included 62 officers and men.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\"/> The regiment was mustered out of service in New York on July 20, 1861. It was remustered on May 28, 1862, under Colonel Martin, and returned to the man the defenses of Washington in 1862.\n\n====Chancellorsville====\nColonel Henry K. Potter commanded the 71st New York State Volunteers (distinct from the 71st NYSNG), which was placed in the Second \"Excelsior\" Brigade (Brig. Gen. Joseph W. Revere) of the Second Division (Maj. Gen. Hiram G. Berry) of the Third Corps (Sickles) in the [[Battle of Chancellorsville]] in May 1863.\n\n====Gettysburg====\nThe 71st passed through [[Chambersburg, Pennsylvania]], on June 23, 1863,<ref>\u201cRachel Cormany Diary.\u201d {{cite web|url=http://etext.virginia.edu/etcbin/browse-valley?id%3DFD1006%26images%3Dimages%2Fmodeng%2FF%26data%3D%2Ftexts%2Fenglish%2Fcivilwar%2Fdiaries%26tag%3Dpublic |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-01-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050407162315/http://etext.virginia.edu/etcbin/browse-valley?id=FD1006&images=images%2Fmodeng%2FF&data=%2Ftexts%2Fenglish%2Fcivilwar%2Fdiaries&tag=public |archivedate=2005-04-07 }}</ref> it is often confused with the 71st New York Volunteers, an entirely separate, three year volunteer regiment, which fought at the [[Battle of Gettysburg]], as part of Sickle's III Corps, again in the Second \"Excelsior\" Brigade (Colonel [[William R. Brewster]]). The 71st militia served in the defense of Harrisburg during the battle of Gettysburg.\n\n====Return to New York====\nAfter the battle, the 71st was recalled to New York City to help suppress the 1863 draft riots (the militia unit that was mobilized to defend Harrisburg, not the volunteer unit that was involved with the actual battle at Gettysburg). The regiment was mustered out of service in 1864. Many members of the 71st joined the 124th New York, which carried on the name \"The American Guard.\" and took part in the Petersburg campaign. Others joined other regiments.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n===State duty===\nThe 71st also served to control the Orange riots of 1871, the railroad riots of July 1877, the switchmen's strike in Buffalo of August 1892, and the motorman's strike of 1895 in [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"DNMA\" />\n\nIn 1884, under accusations of financial mismanagement by Colonel Vose, 15 company-grade officers resigned. Colonel Vose blamed the problems on the Veterans Association.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1884/02/15/106142734.pdf |accessdate=January 15, 2008 |work=The New York Times |title=Laying The Blame On Col. Vose.; Fifteen Line Officers Of The Seventy-First Regiment Resign |date=February 15, 1884}}</ref>\n\nIn 1894, the 71st, under the command of Colonel Francis Vinton Greene, moved into its armory at 33rd and Park Avenue.<ref name=\"New York Times, April 1, 1894\" />\n\n===Spanish\u2013American War===\nIn the [[Spanish\u2013American War]], the 71st Regiment, New York Volunteers, were the first of twelve New York State regiments called to active service on May 10, 1898.<ref name=\"DNMA\" /> The regiment entrained to [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] on May 13, arriving on May 17. A week of confusion and quartermaster incompetence delayed their shipment to Cuba. The 71st was bivouacked along with the 1st U.S. Volunteer Cavalry, the \"Rough Riders\", in Tampa, who then stole a march on the 71st to steal their transport on the ''Tampa.'' The 71st's sea trip took two weeks<ref name=\"DNMA\"/> The confusion of this organization was cited as one of the reasons for the 1903 reforms of the Army and National Guard.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nThere were ten companies of the regiment, with 1,000 soldiers, organized into three battalions.\n\nArriving at Siboney, Cuba, on June 23, the 71st was brigaded with two regular regiments, the 6th and 16th Infantry Regiments in the First Brigade under Regular Army Brigadier General [[Hamilton S. Hawkins]], as part of General [[Jacob Ford Kent]]'s division, as part of the Fifth Corps under General Shafter. Although the 71st was regarded as one of the best National Guard regiments, it was equipped with obsolescent black powder rifles, and its commanding officer, Lieutenant Colonel Wallace A. Downs, reported that one-third of his men had never fired a rifle before.<ref name=millis>Millis, Walter. ''The Martial Spirit''. 1931, Ayer Publishing. p. 285. Accessed through Google Books.</ref>\n\nThe 71st was ordered to support the Rough Riders in a skirmish against Siboney's garrison, but the fighting was over before the New Yorkers could arrive. On June 27, the brigade moved towards Santiago, making slow progress over poor roads in the heat.<ref name=\"DNMA\" /> A letter from a private in the 71st noted \"Yesterday the line of march up the hill was strewn with blankets and extra clothing, even some of the 'regs' [U.S. Regulars] discarded clothes and walked in underwear.\"<ref name=Website>{{cite web |title=Private Oscar Hochstadter  of the 71st New York Volunteer Infantry Writes Home |url=http://www.spanamwar.com/71stNYletterhochstadter.html|publisher=The Spanish American War Centennial Website |accessdate=2012-11-02}}</ref>\n\n====The Battle of Santiago====\nThe regiment took part in the Battle of Santiago ([[Battle of San Juan Hill]]), though it did not take part in the attack. By now many members of the regiment were ill with malaria.<ref>Bates, William Graves (Colonel). \"A Summary of the History of the 71st Infantry, N.G.N.Y.\" In {{cite book|title=Seventy-first New York in the world war|url=https://archive.org/details/seventyfirstnew00sutlgoog|accessdate=2 November 2012|year=1922|publisher=J. J. Little & Ives|page=[https://archive.org/details/seventyfirstnew00sutlgoog/page/n580 516]}}</ref> The road on which Kent's First Brigade moved forked just before coming out of forested areas, and Kent ordered the 71st to take the left-hand road to join the 6th and 16th's left flank. As the regiment left the forest, the 71st was pinned down by accurate Spanish rifle fire from the heights of San Juan hill, preventing any advance.<ref name=\"millis\" />{{rp|285}}\n\nGeneral Hawkins wrote later that General Kent had the 71st detached from his brigade without his knowledge and contrary to his plans and intentions. His command post was two miles (3&nbsp;km) away and through a thick jungle of cactus.<ref name=\"times1900\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1900/01/29/archives/vindicates-71st-regiment-gen-hawkins-contradicts-the-testimony-of.html |work=The New York Times |title=VINDICATES 71ST REGIMENT; Gen. Hawkins Contradicts the Testimony of Gen. Kent. NO NOTICE OF CHANGED PLANS Says Trouble at San Juan Was Due to Men Being Taken Out of His Brigade Without His Knowledge |date=January 29, 1900}}</ref>\n\nSeveral commentators, including Lieutenant Colonel Philip Reade, Inspector General for General Kent, made disparaging remarks about the 71st's apparent lack of courage (though the malaria and heat were contributing factors). The official report of the 13th Infantry, leading Kent's Second Brigade, noted<blockquote>The men of the 71st were lying flat on the ground along the underbrush bordering the road with their feet toward the middle of the road... From the remarks they made to us all along the line as we passed them at a run, I inferred that they were in this prostrate formation for the purpose of avoiding exposure to bullets.<ref name=millis />{{rp|286}}</blockquote>\n\nThe regiment's commander, Lt. Colonel Downs, testified at a court of inquiry in 1899 that he had received no orders to advance since 10 a.m. and therefore held his men in reserve. He said the attack by Lawton's brigade on the right had been delayed, and Downs' last orders had been to wait until Lawton's attack was successful before moving forward. Colonel Reade <ref name=\"times1900\"/>  testified that he had to \"shove\" the 71st into the fight, though Company F commander Captain Malcolm Rafferty and 3rd Battalion commander Major Frank Keck responded immediately. Other men of the regiment also moved forward to join the regulars in the attack,<ref name=\"times1899\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1899/01/15/archives/71st-regiment-inquiry-several-witnesses-testify-in-favor-of-lieut.html |work=The New York Times |title=71ST REGIMENT INQUIRY; Several Witnesses Testify in Favor of Lieut. Col. Smith. TESTIMONY OF ONE EXPUNGED Lieut. Col. Reade's Report on the Conduct of the Command at Santiago Forwarded |date=January 15, 1899}}</ref> but historian Walter Millis noted that \"although the regiment as a whole soon recovered its morale, it had earned a black mark which the censorious publics who hadn't been there could not afterward forgive.\"<ref name=\"millis\" />{{rp|285}} Ironically, the first American soldier to reach the crest of San Juan Hill was Lieutenant Herbert Hyde True of Company L of the 71st (in Keck's battalion).<ref>True, Herbert Hyde. \"Sanguinary San Juan Hill.\" pp 121-122 in Buel, James William. ''Hero Tales of the American Soldier and Sailor as Told by the Heroes'' 1899, A. Holloway. Original from Harvard University Digitized October 16, 2007</ref>\n\n[[image:71st Infantry Regiment at NY Camp Wikoff in 1898.ogv|thumb|left|71st Infantry marching at [[Theodore Roosevelt County Park#Camp Wikoff|Camp Wikoff]], Long Island, NY, after returning from Cuba, September 1898. The picture shows many of the companies reduced to seven or eight men, and the whole regiment, rank and file is in a sad condition.]]\nThe Spanish garrison of Santiago surrendered on July 14, 1898. The 71st began to suffer many men sick from [[yellow fever]] and other tropical diseases. One lieutenant noted there were reports the regiment would be moved to Montauk Point, Long Island, to recuperate from the climate,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/12/weekinreview/word-for-word-letters-home-the-myriad-ways-in-which-war-has-been-hell.html |work=The New York Times |first=Joyce |last=Jensen |title=Word for Word/Letters Home; The Myriad Ways in Which War Has Been Hell |date=November 12, 2000}}</ref> and many men from the 71st were sent there to recover on the hospital ship ''Shinnecock''.<ref>\"More Sick from Montauk\" ''New York Times'', September 17, 1898{{full citation needed|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n\nUpon its return to New York State on August 22, the regiment could only muster 350 of its initial 1,000 men. Eighty men had been killed in the fighting around Santiago. The majority of the regiment was on sick leave or in the hospital. In October the 71st returned to Camp Black and on November 14, 1898, the regiment was mustered out.<ref name=\"DNMA\"/>\n\nFollowing the war, a board of inquiry was held at the 22nd Regiment on the conduct of the senior officers of the regiment, including Lieutenant Colonel Clinton H. Smith, the First Battalion commander. The testimony of witnesses was favorable to Lt. Col. Smith, noting he was present on the battlefield.<ref name=\"times1899\"/> However, Colonel Downs and Major John Whittle resigned their commissions. Two more officers were reprimanded. The board was reviewed by then Governor [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who noted \"the greater part of the Seventy-First of their own free will took part in the storming of San Juan hill, and showed that no matter how cowardly their officers might be, they were willing to obey their country's call.\"<ref>Harrison, W.B. ''Great Round World and what is Going on in it.''vol 10 (1899), pp 737\u2013738</ref>\n\nDespite the bad impression the regiment made as a whole in Santiago, many individual soldiers in the regiment were recognized for courage, including Corporal Lewis Benedict of Co. K (also in Keck's battalion), who \"received a commission as lieutenant in the regular service.\" Major Keck received a commission as a captain in the Regular Army and served in the Philippines.<ref>[http://www.phigam.org/history/Lists/spamwar.htm Phi Gamma Delta in the Spanish American War] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221014347/http://www.phigam.org/history/Lists/spamwar.htm |date= February 21, 2008 }}, accessed 1-15-2008</ref> After the war, Keck became prominent in New York City's social and business life. Another member of the 71st was Charles Johnson Post, who painted memorable watercolor paintings of the 71st in the 1898 war.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0FMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=24+USS+Maine+Burials&cd=8#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=LIFE|date=7 July 1958|publisher=Time Inc|via=Google Books|title = A Little War With A Big Result |pages = }}</ref>\n\n===The new armory===\nThe original armory of the regiment burned down in 1902. A new armory was built on the spot in 1905 by the firm of [[Clinton and Russell]], and was noted for its particularly fine exterior architecture.<ref>[http://www.andrewcusack.com/blog/2007/01/ Andrew Cusack] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104040320/http://www.andrewcusack.com/blog/2007/01/ |date=January 4, 2008 }}. Retrieved 01-16-2008.</ref> This armory was used not only for military training, but many public events such as annual stamp shows.\n\n===World War I===\nIn 1916, before the U.S. entry into [[World War I]], the 71st was mobilized as part of the U.S. Army force serving on the Mexican border.  The 71st mustered in on June 26, 1916, at New York City and mustered out at New York City on October 6, 1916.<ref>New York Mexican Punitive Campaign Muster Rolls for National Guard{{full citation needed|date=January 2020}}</ref> On March 25, 1917 the regiment was federalized,<ref>Sutliffe, p. 7</ref> but in August was required to provide 350 men to the [[69th Infantry Regiment (United States)|69th New York Infantry Regiment]], which was soon to fight overseas as the 165th Infantry Regiment.<ref>Sutliffe, p. 21</ref> On September 30, 1917, the 71st paraded down Fifth Avenue; however, the next day the regiment was \"skeletonized\" to provide cadre for other units, and was denied the opportunity to fight as a unit.<ref>Sutliffe, pp. 29-39</ref> Several of the officers and 1,375 enlisted men of the regiment were transferred to the [[105th Infantry Regiment (United States)|105th Infantry]], with the remainder were transferred to other elements of the [[27th Infantry Division (United States)|27th Division]] and other units.<ref>\"Lieut. H.H. Street Wounded; Served on Mexican Border with Old 71st\", ''New York Times'', August 14, 1918.</ref><ref name=Sut1/> After serving overseas with that division and other units, the 71st regiment's soldiers returned to New York in May 1919 and the unit was re-formed in the New York National Guard.<ref>\"Dozen Ships on Way With More Troops.\" ''New York Times'', May 27, 1919</ref>\n\nMen of the 71st served in Belgium and France during WWI with units of the 27th Division;<ref>Sutliffe, p. 522</ref> Joseph M. Cahill was in G Company (presumably of the 105th Infantry) and his military record lists the following battles: Hindenburg Line, John Oder Mer Ridge, La Salle River, and the following engagements: The Knoll, Gillimont Farm, Quennemont Farm, St. Maurice River, Viertaat Ridge, and finally the following Minor Actions East: Poperinohe Line and Dickebusch Sector.\n\nA partial listing of awards and commendations appears in Robert S. Sutliffe's ''Seventy-First New York in the World War'' (which can be seen on Google Books), it includes 11 US Army [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]es, 137 divisional citations, as well as 8 British decorations, 7 French decorations, 4 Belgium decorations, and Montenegrin Decorations.<ref>Sutliffe, pp. 367-401</ref>\n\n===Between the World Wars===\nFrom 1921-41, the 71st was brigaded with the 174th Infantry Regiment as part of the [[87th Infantry Brigade (United States) |87th Infantry Brigade]], [[44th Infantry Division (United States)|44th Infantry Division]].<ref>{{cite book|first = John J. |last = McGrath|title = The Brigade: A History|page =171|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KWrLJj-iTlAC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA171| publisher = DIANE Publishing |date = 2004|isbn =9781428910225}}</ref> It performed a number of civil and ceremonial duties. Its annual training was usually at [[Camp Smith (New York)|Camp Smith]] in [[Peekskill, New York]]. Its regimental armory served as a homeless shelter in 1934.<ref>\"Armory Is Opened To Homeless Men 71st And Two Others Will Be Used As Day-Time Shelter.\" ''New York Times'', December 18, 1934</ref> The 1940 and 1941 annual training took place at Fort Dix, New Jersey.\n\n===World War II===\nIn World War II, the 71st, consisting of three battalions, was part of the [[44th Infantry Division (United States)|44th Infantry Division]], which assembled at [[Fort Lewis, Washington]]. Headquarters Company of the 1st Battalion was detached to take part in the [[Battle of Attu|retaking of Attu Island]] in the [[Aleutian campaign]].  The 102d Engr Bn (CBT) also had its Company C serving in the Pacific Campaign.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nSergeant [[Charles A. MacGillivary]] of the 71st received the [[Medal of Honor]] for actions during the German Ardennes offensive of December 1944 near Woelfling, France, near the German border. On January 1, 1944, Sergeant MacGillivary was serving as company commander because of casualties among the officers. Ammunition was low and the company was pinned down. MacGillivary set out on his own to destroy the German machine guns menacing his company. He carried a sub-machine gun and grenades; when his submachine gun ran out of ammunition, he picked up a discarded weapon and continued the attack. MacGillivary wiped out the German positions and killed or wounded all of the defenders, at the cost of his left arm.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/06/30/us/c-a-macgillivary-83-dies-won-medal-of-honor.html |work=The New York Times |first=Richard |last=Goldstein |title=C. A. MacGillivary, 83, Dies; Won Medal of Honor |date=June 30, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn this offensive, the 71st encountered the [[17th SS Panzergrenadier Division G\u00f6tz von Berlichingen]], holding off eight attacks.\n\nThe Second Battalion and I Company of the Third Battatlion were both awarded [[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Presidential Unit Citation]]s.\n\nIn the last days of the war, the First Battalion crossed the Austrian border through a mountain pass and attacked a German division.\n\n===After World War II===\nThe 71st was not called to active duty in either the Korean War or the Vietnam War. It was called to state active duty in April 1979 to serve as prison guards at Taconic and [[Bedford Hills Correctional Facility for Women|Bedford Hills prison]]s during a correctional officers' strike.\n\nThe regiment's original armory was located at Park Avenue and 34th Street in Manhattan. It later moved to 125 West 14th Street.\n\nIn 1984, the Governor of New York, [[Mario Cuomo]], proposed disbanding the 71st and 106th Infantry to use their armory spaces for civilian purposes. The 71st Infantry Veterans' Association sued the state in court, stating that such realignment would violate state affirmative action guidelines since the 71st Infantry was predominantly black. The 71st received a favorable ruling.<ref>\"Court Order Rescues Historic Guard Unit,\" ''New York Times'', February 2, 1984</ref>\n\nOn August 31, 1993, the 71st disbanded as a National Guard unit.<ref name=\"veteran\"/> A detachment of the battalion in Batavia, New York, was kept on active duty.<ref>\"136 Guardsmen to stay active despite units' status\", ''Buffalo News'', February 12, 1993</ref> The First Battalion became a [[State Guard]] unit, serving with the 14th Infantry Brigade.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/09/AR2006080900262_pf.html |accessdate=January 14, 2008|title=U.S. Forces Repel Raid on Afghan Base |last=Garwood|first=Paul |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Symbols and traditions==\nThe regimental nickname is \"The American Guard.\" The regimental motto is \"Pro aris et pro focis,\" which can be translated \"For our homes and our families\" but see '[[Pro aris et focis]]'. The regimental march is \"The Gallant Seventy-First.\"\n\nThe regimental crest is a blue shield, edged in gold, charged with gold fasces with the ax head pointing to the left, supported by two gold crescents. (This is the opposite direction from the Italian fascist symbol.)<ref>[http://dmna.ny.gov/historic/heraldry/arngdui/71stInfantry.htm Heraldry: 71st Infantry]. New York State Military Museum. Retrieved July 31, 2013</ref>\n\nThe commanding officer of the regiment traditionally wore as his ceremonial sidearm a Colt revolver that was originally Colonel Martin's sidearm. This pistol was left with the senior officer of the regiment (or later, battalion) in the commanding officer's absence.\n\n==Commanding officers==\nDates in parentheses are known dates, but not start or ending dates.\n* Colonel Abram S. Vosburgh, 1852\u20131861\n* Colonel Henry P. Martin, 1861\u20131862\n* Colonel Charles H. Smith, 1862\u20131863\n* Colonel H.L. Trafford, 1863\u20131866\n* Colonel Theodore W. Parmalee, 1866\u20131869\n* Colonel Henry Rockafeller, 1869\u20131871\n* Colonel Richard Vose, 1871\u20131884\n* Colonel [[Edwin A. McAlpin]], 1885\n* Colonel Frederick Kopper, 1891\n* Colonel [[Francis Vinton Greene]], 1891\n* Colonel Johnathan T. Camp (1895)\n* Lieutenant Colonel Wallace A. Downs (1898)\u20131899\n* Colonel Walter Delamater (1936)\n\n==See also==\n* [[71st Infantry Regiment (United States)]]\n* [[Spanish American War Monument to the 71st Infantry Regiment]]\n* [[Joyce's 71st New York Regiment March]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Post, Charles Johnson. ''The Little War of Private Post: The Spanish\u2013American War Seen Up Close''. 1999, University of Nebraska Press. 352 pages. {{ISBN|0-8032-8757-7}}\n* Lieutenant Colonel Thomas Rafferty, Personal Recollections of the War of the Rebellion, Titled \"Gettysburg\" pages 1\u201332.\n* {{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/seventyfirstnewy00sutl|title=Seventy-first New York in the world war|first=Robert Stewart|last=Sutliffe|date=22 March 2018|publisher=New York, Printed by J. J. Little & Ives co.|via=Internet Archive}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the United States in the Spanish\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:United States Army regiments in World War II]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Civil War regiments|Infantry 071]]\n[[Category:Excelsior Brigade]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:State defense forces of the United States|New York, 71st Infantry Regiment]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:1850 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1850]]\n", "name_user": "Can I Log In", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing bad spacing with reference footnotes (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/71st_New_York_Infantry"}
{"title_page": "2020 New England Patriots season", "text_new": "{{short description|61st season in franchise history}}\n{{Infobox NFL season\n| team            = New England Patriots\n| logo            = New England Patriots wordmark.svg\n| year            = 2020\n| record          = \n| division_place  = \n| playoffs        = \n| coach           = [[Bill Belichick]]\n| owner           = [[Robert Kraft]]\n| general manager = [[Bill Belichick]]\n| stadium         = [[Gillette Stadium]]\n| radio           = \n| uniform         = \n| shortnavlink    = Patriots seasons\n}}\nThe [[2020 NFL season|2020 season]] will be the [[New England Patriots]]' upcoming 51st season in the [[National Football League]], their 61st overall and their 21st under [[List of New England Patriots head coaches|head coach]] [[Bill Belichick]]. \n\nIt will also be the first season since [[1999 New England Patriots season|1999]] without long-time quarterback [[Tom Brady]] on the roster and the first since [[2000 New England Patriots season|2000]] without Brady as starting quarterback, who announced he would leave the team in free agency on March 17 via social media and subsequently signed with the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]. Believed by many as the greatest quarterback of all time, Brady led the Patriots to 9 Super Bowl appearances, winning 6 of them from the [[2001 New England Patriots season|2001]] to [[2018 New England Patriots season|2018]] seasons, and had been their starting quarterback from September 30, 2001 until the team's final game in 2019 (except during the [[2008 New England Patriots season|2008 season]] when Brady when was on the [[Injured reserve list|IR list]] due to a combined [[Anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]]/[[Medial collateral ligament|MCL]] tear).<ref>{{cite news|last=Patra|first=Kevin|title=Tom Brady officially signs contract with Buccaneers|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001107130/article/tom-brady-officially-signs-contract-with-buccaneers|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=NFL.com|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Scott|title=All in! Tom Brady, Bucs team up to pursue championships|url=https://www.buccaneers.com/news/tom-brady-qb-buccaneers-free-agency-roster-move|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Buccaneers.com|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> On April 20, the Patriots made their color rush jerseys to their primary jersey, and changed the design of their away jerseys.\n\nThe Patriots will attempt to improve on their [[2019 New England Patriots season|12\u20134 record]] from the previous year and win their 12th consecutive [[AFC East]] title.\n\n== Roster changes ==\n\n=== Free agency ===\n\n==== Unrestricted ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|New England Patriots|year=2020|border=2}}\" |Position\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|New England Patriots|year=2020|border=2}}\" |Player\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|New England Patriots|year=2020|border=2}}\" |2020 team\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|New England Patriots|year=2020|border=2}}\" |Date signed\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|New England Patriots|year=2020|border=2}}\" |Contract\n|-style=\"background:#fcc\"\n|[[Quarterback|QB]]\n|[[Tom Brady]]\n|[[2020 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n|March 20, 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rostermon.com/player/83/|title=Tom Brady|website=rostermon.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|2 years, $50 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spotrac.com/nfl/tampa-bay-buccaneers/tom-brady-4619/|title=Tom Brady|last=Spotrac.com|website=Spotrac.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-style=\"background:#cfc\"\n|[[Defensive end|DE]]\n|[[Shilique Calhoun]]\n|New England Patriots\n|March 24, 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rostermon.com/player/6057/|title=Shilique Calhoun|website=rostermon.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|1 year, $1.5 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spotrac.com/nfl/