134<ref>{{cite web|author=Ron Florax |url=http://cuetracker.net/tournaments/pontins-pro-am-event-1/2008/2337 |title=2008 Pontins Pro-Am \u2013 Event 1 \u2013 Snooker Results & Statistics |publisher=CueTracker |date=1 January 2008 |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 3.\n| 2008\n| Pontins Pro-Am Event 3\n| {{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Peter Lines]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20134<ref>{{cite web|author=Ron Florax |url=http://cuetracker.net/tournaments/pontins-pro-am-event-3/2008/2339 |title=2008 Pontins Pro-Am \u2013 Event 3 \u2013 Snooker Results & Statistics |publisher=CueTracker |date=1 January 2008 |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner\n| 4.\n| 2009\n| Pontins Pro-Am Event 3 <small>(2)</small>\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Peter Lines]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\u20132<ref>{{cite web|author=Ron Florax |url=http://cuetracker.net/tournaments/pontins-pro-am-event-3/2009/2346 |title=2009 Pontins Pro-Am \u2013 Event 3 \u2013 Snooker Results & Statistics |publisher=CueTracker |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner\n| 5.\n| 2010\n| [[Austrian Open (snooker)|Austrian Open]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Neil Robertson]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\u20134\n|}\n\n===Amateur finals: 1 (1 title)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:80px;\"|'''Outcome'''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|'''No.'''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:50px;\"|'''Year'''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:200px;\"|'''Championship'''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:200px;\"|'''Opponent in the final'''\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:50px;\"|'''Score'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| 2004\n| English Open\n| {{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Craig Steadman]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\u20137<ref>{{cite web|title=Other Tournaments Until 2020|url=http://bgsnooker.com/blog/%D1%82%D1%83%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B8/%D0%B4%D1%80%D1%83%D0%B3%D0%B8-%D1%82%D1%83%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B8/%D0%B4%D1%80%D1%83%D0%B3%D0%B8-%D1%82%D1%83%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B8-%D0%BE%D1%82-2010/#t4|publisher=bgsnooker.com|accessdate=3 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103074138/http://bgsnooker.com/blog/%D1%82%D1%83%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B8/%D0%B4%D1%80%D1%83%D0%B3%D0%B8-%D1%82%D1%83%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B8/%D0%B4%D1%80%D1%83%D0%B3%D0%B8-%D1%82%D1%83%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B8-%D0%BE%D1%82-2010/#t4|archive-date=3 January 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Judd Trump}}\n* [http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/judd-trump/ Judd Trump] at ''worldsnooker.com''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091130004335/http://www.global-snooker.com/Judd-Trump.asp Global Snooker profile]\n\n{{World snooker champions}}\n{{Snooker world number ones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trump, Judd}}\n[[Category:English snooker players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bristol]]\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:World number one snooker players]]\n[[Category:UK champions (snooker)]]\n[[Category:Masters (snooker) champions]]\n[[Category:Winners of the professional snooker world championship]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English professional snooker player, 2019 world champion}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| image          = Judd Trump May 2015.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = Trump at the 2015 World Championship\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1989|8|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Whitchurch, Bristol|Whitchurch]], [[Bristol]], [[England]]\n| Sport country  = {{ENG}}\n| Nickname       =\n Mr. Haircut 100<ref name=\"World Snooker (2007, Judd Trump)\">{{cite web | title= Player List \u2013 Judd Trump | publisher= [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] | year= 2009 | url= http://www.worldsnooker.com/player_list-9926.htm | accessdate= 3 January 2010 | archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/5mVT5H43u?url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/player_list-9926.htm | archivedate= 3 January 2010 | url-status= live | df= dmy-all }}</ref><br />(The) Ace (in the Pack)<ref>{{cite web |title=Judd Trump |website=World Snooker |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/Judd-Trump/ |accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC Sport (2007, 1 May)\">{{cite news|first=Saj |last=Chowdhury |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=1 May 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6612887.stm |title=The man behind the nicknames |accessdate=2 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PH7ZeyyS?url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6612887.stm |archivedate= 2 May 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title = Snooker: Players Championship Live |series = World Snooker |network = ITV |station = ITV4 HD |date = 28 February 2020 |minutes = 16}}</ref><br /> Danny the Boy<ref name=\"eusp\">{{cite web | date=20 February 2009 | title = Right on cue: Judd Trump | work=[[Eurosport]] | url = https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/right-on-cue-judd-trump_sto1850672/story.shtml | accessdate = 26 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919012440/https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/right-on-cue-judd-trump_sto1850672/story.shtml |archive-date=2016-09-19 |url-status=live}}</ref><br />Judd Triumph<ref name=\"eusp\" /><br />Juddernaut<ref name=\"Hart\">{{cite news |last1=Hart |first1=Simon |title=World Championship 2011: Judd 'The Juddernaut' Trump is building the momentum to reach his first final |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/8481855/World-Championship-2011-Judd-The-Juddernaut-Trump-is-building-the-momentum-to-reach-his-first-final.html |accessdate=8 May 2019 |date=28 April 2011 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n| Professional   = 2005\u2013\n| High ranking   = '''[[List of world number one snooker players|1]]''' {{smaller|(November\u2013December 2012, February\u2013March 2013, August 2019\u2013)}}\n| Prize money    = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]4,089,754\n| High break     = '''[[Maximum break|147]]''' {{smaller|(4 times)<ref name=\"worldsnooker.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/wpbsa/official-147s/ |title=Official 147s \u2013 World Snooker |accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>}}\n| Century break  = 712\n| Ranking wins   = 17\n| Minor wins     = 4\n| Other wins     = 6\n| World champ    = [[2019 World Snooker Championship|2019]]\n}}\n\n'''Judd Trump''' (born 20 August 1989)<ref name=\"groveleisurejuddtrump\">{{cite web|title=Grove Leisure Judd Trump|url=http://www.grovesnooker.co.uk/snookerplayers/judd-trump/|work=grovesnooker.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> is an [[English people|English]] professional [[snooker]] player from [[Bristol]] who is the [[2019 World Snooker Championship|reigning World Champion]] and the current [[List of world number one snooker players|world number one]]. One of 11 players in the history of the sport to win all [[Triple Crown (snooker)|Triple Crown]] events at least once, he has won a career total of 17 ranking titles, putting him in joint seventh place (with [[Mark Selby]]) on the [[List of snooker players by number of ranking titles|all-time list]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wst.tv/six-of-the-best-trump-sets-new-record/|title=Six Of The Best - Trump Sets New Record|date=2020-03-15|website=World Snooker|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nAfter winning the English Under-13 and Under-15 championships, and reaching the World Under-21 Championship semi-finals, Trump turned professional in 2005, aged 16. He captured his first ranking title at the [[2011 China Open (snooker)|2011 China Open]], defeating Selby 10\u20138 in the final. The following month, he reached the final of the [[2011 World Snooker Championship|2011 World Championship]], but lost 15\u201318 to [[John Higgins]]. He claimed his first Triple Crown title later that year when he won the [[2011 UK Championship (snooker)|2011 UK Championship]], defeating [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] 10\u20138 in the final.\n\nBy the end of the [[2017\u201318 snooker season]], Trump had won a total of eight ranking titles, although many believed that he had underachieved up to that point in his career, given his talent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/46321041|title=UK Championship: Judd Trump - nine ranking titles, but has he underachieved?|date=2018-11-26|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-03-16|language=en-GB}}</ref> During the [[2018\u201319 snooker season]], his form and focus notably improved. In addition to ranking titles at the [[2018 Northern Ireland Open|Northern Ireland Open]] and the [[2019 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]], he won his first [[2019 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] title, defeating [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 10\u20134 in the final, and completed his Triple Crown by winning his first [[2019 World Snooker Championship|World Snooker Championship]], defeating Higgins 18\u20139 in what some commentators described as the highest-quality world final ever played.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Championship final \u2013 reaction as Trump beats Higgins 18\u20139|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/snooker/47311519|date=2019-05-06 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/snooker/2019/05/06/judd-trump-wins-world-championship-victory-john-higgins-highest/ |title=Judd Trump wins World Championship with victory over John Higgins in highest-quality final ever seen |date=6 May 2019 |first=Jeremy |last=Wilson |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |access-date=8 May 2019}}</ref> He also became the first snooker player to win over \u00a31 million in prize money in a single season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/05/06/judd-trumps-record-breaking-prize-money-season-winning-snooker-world-championship-9421300/|title=Judd Trump's record breaking prize money after Snooker World Championship win|date=2019-05-06|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019\u201320 snooker season]] so far, Trump has won six ranking tournaments, setting a new record for the most ranking titles in a single season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/51901514|title=Gibraltar Open: Judd Trump wins sixth ranking title of season|date=2020-03-15|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-03-16|language=en-GB}}</ref> A prolific break-builder, he has compiled more than 700 [[century break]]s in professional competition, making him the youngest player to achieve this feat and only the fifth player ever to reach the 700-century mark.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/snooker-news-judd-trump-hits-700th-century-break-at-championship-league_sto7693104/story.shtml |title=Trump hits record-breaking 700th century break at Championship League |date=2020-03-05 |first=Desmond |last=Kane |work=Eurosport |access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTrump was English Under-13 and Under-15 champion, and reached the World Under-21 Championship semi-finals at the age of 14. At the same age, he became the youngest player to make a competitive 147.<ref name=\"eusp\" />\n\n===Turning professional (2005/2006)===\nTrump joined the professional tour in the [[Snooker season 2005/2006|2005/2006 season]], and at the [[2006 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] became the youngest player ever to qualify for the final stages of a ranking tournament. He also reached the last-48 stage at the [[2006 China Open (snooker)|China Open]], losing 4\u20135 to [[Michael Holt (snooker player)|Michael Holt]], although this was designated the final qualifying round and was actually played in [[Prestatyn]], Wales.<ref>{{cite web|title=Judd Trump \u2013 Season 2005\u20132006 \u2013 Professional Results|url=http://cuetracker.net/Players/judd-trump/2005-2006|publisher=Cue Tracker|accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe defeated [[James Wattana]] 10\u20135 in the final round of qualifying at the [[2007 World Snooker Championship|2007 World Championship]], to become the third-youngest player (at the time) ever to reach the main stage of the tournament (champions [[Stephen Hendry]] and [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] had both been younger when they made their Crucible debuts). Trump is one of only five players to make their first appearance at Sheffield's Crucible Theatre at the age of 17 (along with Hendry, O'Sullivan, China's [[Liu Chuang (snooker player)|Liu Chuang]] and Belgium's [[Luca Brecel]]). He played the 2005 champion and sixth seed, [[Shaun Murphy]], in the first round, but lost 6\u201310 despite having led 6\u20135 earlier in the match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Judd Trump|url=http://www.prosnookerblog.com/players/s-t/judd-trump/|publisher=Pro Snooker|accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe did not build on this form in the [[Snooker season 2007/2008|2007/2008 season]], only reaching the last 32 of the [[2008 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] by beating [[Joe Swail]] 5\u20132 in the first round. He also missed out on the [[2008 World Snooker Championship|2008 World Championship]] after a 9\u201310 loss to Swail in the final round of qualifying, despite having led 9\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|title=Head-to-Head: Joe Swail vs Judd Trump|url=http://cuetracker.net/Head-to-Head/joe-swail/judd-trump|publisher=Cue Tracker|accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nTrump's fortunes changed for the [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/2009 season]] when he reached the venue stages of the first four events. At the [[2008 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], he benefited from [[Graeme Dott]]'s withdrawal before defeating [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]] 5\u20132 in the last 16, despite Perry feeling that he had outplayed Trump, who himself admitted to not having played well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/royal_london_watches_grand_prix_news-8321.htm?tid=113|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305234408/http://www.worldsnooker.com/royal_london_watches_grand_prix_news-8321.htm?tid=113|url-status=dead|title=Top Trump|archivedate=5 March 2012}}</ref> Then came the biggest win of his career so far, when he defeated Ronnie O'Sullivan 5\u20134 to reach the semi-final, in which he was himself defeated 4\u20136 by [[John Higgins]]. He beat double world champion [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] to qualify for the [[2008 Bahrain Championship]]. He won a [[Masters Qualifying Event|qualifying event]] in 2008 to gain entry into the [[2009 Masters (snooker)|2009 Masters]] as the only qualifier, but was defeated by [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] in the first round. He again failed to reach the main stage of the World Championship, losing 8\u201310 to [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] in the final qualifying round, having led 6\u20133. Lee noted that Trump had not followed the custom of apologising for fluked shots during the match, and concluded \"all I've heard about for the last five years in my area is how good he is, and he is good .. but he's blown a 6\u20133 lead today and hopefully that will stick with him for a while yet.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=World Championship: final qualifying |magazine=Snooker Scene magazine |page=11 |publisher=Everton's News Agency |date=April 2009 }}</ref> Trump ended the season in the Top 32 of the rankings for the first time. He was coached for a short time by [[Tony Chappel]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Judd Trump|url=http://spainprosnooker.es/en/judd-trump/|publisher=Spain Snooker|accessdate=13 September 2016|date=23 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe won the [[2009 Championship League]] to qualify for the [[2009 Premier League Snooker|Premier League]] event later in the year, in which he won four of his six matches including a 4\u20132 win over Ronnie O'Sullivan. He finished second in the League table but lost 1\u20135 to O'Sullivan in his semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Judd Trump|url=http://www.grovesnooker.co.uk/snookerplayers/judd-trump/|publisher=Grove's Snooker|accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Snooker season 2009/2010|2009/2010 season]] was less successful for Trump as he failed to progress beyond the last 32 in any of the ranking tournaments. In January 2010, he joined Romford-based snooker agency Grove Leisure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grovesnooker.co.uk/2010/01/20/judd-trump-joins-the-grove/|title=Judd Trump joins the Grove|date=20 January 2010|publisher=Grove Leisure}}</ref>\n\n===2010/2011===\nTrump defeated former world champions [[Peter Ebdon]] and [[Shaun Murphy]] at the [[2011 China Open (snooker)|2011 China Open]], to reach his first professional ranking event final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grovesnooker.co.uk/2011/04/03/judd-trump-wins-china-open/ |title=Judd Trump wins China Open |date=3 April 2011 |work=Grove Leisure |access-date=2 October 2019}}</ref> He then triumphed over former Masters champion [[Mark Selby]] 10\u20138 to win his first major title.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/china-open-champ-judd-my-career-begins-now/|title=China Open champ Judd: My career begins now |date=3 April 2011 |first=Michael |last=Emons |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]}}</ref> He won \u00a360,000 in prize money and provisionally climbed into the top 16 of the world rankings. On his way to winning the China Open final, Trump made his [[List of snooker players with over 100 century breaks|100th competitive century break]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/13041426 |title=World Snooker 2011: Five players to watch |work=[[BBC Sport]] |access-date=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nTrump had already qualified for the [[2011 World Snooker Championship|2011 World Championship]] when he won the China Open, and was drawn against reigning champion [[Neil Robertson]] in the first round, whom he defeated 10\u20138.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2340516,00.html |title=Champ Crashes To Top Trump |date=2011-04-16 |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612034144/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2340516,00.html |archive-date=2012-06-12 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In subsequent rounds, he knocked out [[Martin Gould]] 13\u20136, [[Graeme Dott]] 13\u20135 and [[Ding Junhui]] 17\u201315 to qualify for his first World Championship final.<ref>{{cite news|title=World Championship scores and results |work=[[BBC Sport]] |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/9390290.stm |accessdate=2019-12-28 |date=}}</ref> He lost the final 15\u201318 to [[John Higgins]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/8488851/World-Snooker-Championship-2011-John-Higgins-wins-fourth-title-as-Judd-Trump-captures-Crucible-crowd.html|title=John Higgins wins fourth title as Judd Trump captures Crucible crowd|date=3 May 2011|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=3 May 2011|location=London|first=Simon|last=Hart}}</ref>\n\n===2011/2012===\nTrump started the season with a 3\u20135 loss to [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]] in the first round of the [[2011 Australian Goldfields Open]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-2015995/Judd-Trump-beaten-Mark-Davis-Goldfields-Open.html | title=Crucible finalist Trump knocked out Down Under after last 32 defeat to Davis | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=12 December 2011 | location=London | date=18 July 2011}}</ref> However, this disappointment was soon forgotten as he won the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 2|second PTC event]] of the season, beating [[Ding Junhui]] 4\u20130 in the final at a virtual home venue of the South West Snooker Academy.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/snooker/14488351.stm | title=Judd Trump beats Ding Junhui to win PTC event | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=12 December 2011 | date=11 August 2011}}</ref> He then lost 1\u20135 against [[Stuart Bingham]] in the [[2011 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] first round.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/sport/other/9240764.In_form_Stuart_to_face_Higgins_after_Judd_win/ | title=In-form Stuart Bingham to face John Higgins after Judd Trupp win |date=2011-09-08 |first=James |last=Colasanti |newspaper=[[The Echo (Essex)|The Echo]] |accessdate=12 December 2011}}</ref> Trump finished runner-up to [[Neil Robertson]] in the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 8|eighth PTC event]] of the season,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://maximumsnooker.com/ptc8_2011_robertson_tops_trump.htm |title=PTC8 2011 \u2013 Robertson Tops Trump |date=2011-10-23 |website=maximumsnooker.com |accessdate=12 December 2011}}</ref> but he immediately rediscovered his winning touch by capturing [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 9|Event 9]] when he overcame [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 4\u20133 in the final in [[Antwerp]], Belgium, in just over an hour's worth of play.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://maximumsnooker.com/ptc9_2011_judd_ace_in_antwerp.htm |title=PTC9 2011 \u2013 Judd Ace In Antwerp |date=2011-11-14 |website=maximumsnooker.com |accessdate=12 December 2011}}</ref> He would later top the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012#Order of Merit|Order of Merit]] after all twelve PTC events had been played, thus qualifying for the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Finals|2012 Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|title=PTC Order of Merit after PTC12 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/ae/98/0,,13165~170158,00.pdf |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=29 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6E1vjJOSK?url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/ae/98/0,,13165~170158,00.pdf |archivedate=29 January 2013 }}</ref> He suffered a shock in the last 16 as world number 51 [[Xiao Guodong]] beat him 4\u20132, despite playing with a broken bone in his hand.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sportinglife.aol.co.uk/news/article/22893/7602214/xiao-knocks-out-judd-trump | title=Xiao Knocks Out Trump | publisher=[[AOL]] | date=16 March 2012 | accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 2011, Trump won his second ranking event tournament, the [[2011 UK Championship (snooker)|2011 UK Championship]] at the [[Barbican Centre, York|Barbican Centre]] in [[York]]. He defeated [[Dominic Dale]] 6\u20134 in the last 32, before winning the final two frames of the second round to edge out Ronnie O'Sullivan, 6\u20135. After the match, Trump claimed that he had been \"outplayed\" and was \"lucky\" to have got through.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/snooker/16059032.stm | title=O'Sullivan quit threat as Trump wins | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=12 December 2011 | date=7 December 2011}}</ref> He then dispatched [[Stephen Maguire]] 6\u20133<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/snooker/16097110.stm | title=Trump sinks Maguire to make semi-final | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=12 December 2011 | date=8 December 2011}}</ref> and faced Neil Robertson in the semi-finals. The semi-final match was a tight and nervy affair, with Trump stating afterwards that he believed Robertson was trying to stifle his natural game by \"slowing it down\" and \"making things awkward\", but nevertheless the [[Bristol]]ian triumphed, 9\u20137 to reach his first UK final.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/snooker/16116320.stm | title=Trump defeats Robertson in semi-final | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=12 December 2011 | date=9 December 2011}}</ref> In the final he played [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] and trailed 1\u20133 early on in the best-of-19-frames match. However, Trump then produced a match-defining run of seven straight frames to take an 8\u20133 lead. Despite a strong fightback from Allen, who won five of the next six frames to trail just 8\u20139, Trump managed to clinch the 18th frame with a break of 91 and won the final 10\u20138.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/8949995/Judd-Trump-holds-off-fightback-from-Mark-Allen-to-take-williamhill.com-UK-Championship-trophy-in-York.html | title=Judd Trump holds off fightback from Mark Allen to take williamhill.com UK Championship trophy in York | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | accessdate=12 December 2011 | location=London | date=11 December 2011}}</ref> Six-time winner of the event, [[Steve Davis]], said that Trump's performances during the championship had shown that he was \"spearheading his generation\" of snooker players.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/snooker/16131999.stm | title=Judd Trump beats Mark Allen to win title | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=12 December 2011 | date=11 December 2011}}</ref> The victory took him up to a career-high world ranking of 5.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/WorldRankingsArticle/0,,13165~2216576,00.html | title=World Rankings | accessdate=12 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nTrump continued his fine form by reaching the semi-finals of the [[2012 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] in January. He defeated Stuart Bingham in the first round and O'Sullivan once more in the quarter-finals 6\u20132, to make his record against the four-time World Champion five wins and two defeats, from their seven meetings in tournament play.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/snooker/16634261.stm | title=Masters Snooker: Judd Trump beats Ronnie O' Sullivan | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=19 January 2012 | accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> He met Robertson in the semi-finals for the second successive major event and it was the Australian who exacted his revenge for the defeat suffered in York a month earlier, as he triumphed 6\u20133.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/snooker/16666412.stm | title=Masters Snooker: Neil Robertson/Shaun Murphy into final | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=21 January 2012 | accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> Trump reached three quarter-finals in his next four ranking events to become the world number 2 in April, behind [[Mark Selby]], meaning that Trump had risen seven places in the rankings this season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=12&season=2011 | title=Judd Trump 2011/2012 | website=snooker.org | accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2012 World Snooker Championship|2012 World Championship]], Trump defeated Dominic Dale in their first round match by a 10\u20137 scoreline, despite suffering from food poisoning.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/apr/25/judd-trump-world-snooker-championship?newsfeed=true | title=Judd Trump overcomes food poisoning to beat Dominic Dale at the Crucible | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=25 April 2012 | accessdate=30 April 2012 | location=London}}</ref> However, he was knocked out in the second round by [[Allister Carter|Ali Carter]] 12\u201313, having let slip a 12\u20139 lead, ending his chances of becoming world number 1 this season.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/17887396 | title=World Snooker Championship 2012: Trump suffers shock defeat | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=30 April 2012 | accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2012/2013===\nTrump started the season at the [[2012 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]] in [[China]], where he lost to [[Robert Milkins]] 3\u20135 in the second round, having beaten [[Dominic Dale]] 5\u20131 in the opener.<ref name=\"2012/13\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=12&season=2012 | title=Judd Trump 2012/2013 | website=snooker.org | accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref> At the [[2012 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] he saw off [[Barry Hawkins]], [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]], [[Graeme Dott]] and [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] to reach the final where he faced [[John Higgins]].<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> Trump surged into a 5\u20130 lead and, despite Higgins making a 147 break in the next frame, claimed a 7\u20132 advantage after the first session.<ref name=\"Higgins/Trump\" /> Upon the resumption of play, Higgins won six frames in a row with the match eventually going into a deciding frame; Trump made a break of 35 but ran out of position, allowing Higgins to secure the title with a 10\u20139 victory.<ref name=\"Higgins/Trump\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/19692139 | title=Shanghai Masters: John Higgins edges Judd Trump in final | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 April 2013| date=23 September 2012 }}</ref> However, Trump was able to bounce back at the next ranking event, the inaugural [[2012 International Championship|International Championship]], by claiming his third ranking event title. He eliminated [[Fergal O'Brien]] 6\u20133, [[Aditya Mehta]] 6\u20130 and then edged past Allen 6\u20135 in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/20166689 | title=Mark Allen defeated 6\u20135 by Judd Trump in China | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 April 2013| date=November 2012 }}</ref> Trump thrashed [[Peter Ebdon]] 9\u20131 in the semi-finals to become snooker's tenth world number one,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/20182609 | title=Judd Trump beats Peter Ebdon to become world number one | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 April 2013| date=2 November 2012 }}</ref> and recovered from 6\u20138 down in the final against [[Neil Robertson]] to triumph 10\u20138.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/nov/04/trump-robertson-international-championship-final | title=Judd Trump beats Neil Robertson in International Championship final | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | accessdate=29 April 2013 | location=London | date=4 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nTrump met John Higgins in back to back [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013|Players Tour Championship]] finals, losing the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 4|first]] 2\u20134, but gained revenge in the second, the [[European Tour 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 4|Bulgarian Open]] by whitewashing him 4\u20130.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> Trump reached the final of the [[2012 Premier League Snooker|Premier League]] having beating Neil Robertson in the semi-finals, but lost 2\u20137 to [[Stuart Bingham]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/8282895/Stuart-Bingham-crowned-Premier-League-champion-after-beating-Judd-Trump-in-final | title=Stuart Bingham crowned Premier League champion after beating Judd Trump in final | date=2012-11-28 |work=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref> In the defence of his 2011 [[2012 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] title, Trump played [[Mark Joyce]] in the first round. Despite leading 3\u20130 and 5\u20132, Trump lost the last four frames of the match to suffer a major shock exit against the world number 50.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/20574183 | title=UK Snooker Championship 2012: Judd Trump loses to Mark Joyce | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 April 2013| date=2 December 2012 }}</ref> The disappointment was compounded when [[Mark Selby]] went on to win the title, reclaiming the top ranking in the process.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/20658965 | title=UK Snooker Championship 2012: Mark Selby beats Shaun Murphy | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 April 2013| date=10 December 2012 }}</ref> Trump was defeated 1\u20136 by Graeme Dott at the [[2013 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] and 4\u20135 by [[Anthony Hamilton (snooker player)|Anthony Hamilton]] in the first round of the [[2013 German Masters|German Masters]].<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> He regained his form and the world number one ranking at the [[2013 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]]. He came back from 1\u20133 down to beat Dominic Dale 4\u20133 in the first round, after which he asserted that \"players are changing their game to play slower against me. Dominic was too slow for himself and it caught him out towards the end\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3075157,00.html | title=Trump Battles Past 'Slow' Dale |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] | date=2013-02-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217095150/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3075157,00.html |archive-date=2013-02-17 |url-status=dead}}</ref> More comfortable victories ensued over [[Andrew Higginson]] and [[Pankaj Arjan Advani|Pankaj Advani]] to set up a semi-final meeting with [[Stephen Maguire]].<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> Trump initially raced into a 2\u20130 lead only to lose five frames in succession to the rejuvenated Maguire. Trump pulled back two more frames and looked set to force a decider after a 50 break in the tenth frame, but Maguire ground out the frame and won the match 6\u20134.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nAt the [[2013 World Open (snooker)|World Open]], Trump gained revenge over Joyce by dispatching him 5\u20130 and beat [[Nigel Bond]] 5\u20131, before [[Matthew Stevens]] won their last eight match 5\u20133.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/8531312/Haikou-World-Open-Matthew-Stevens-beats-Judd-Trump-after-getting-own-cue-back | title=Haikou World Open: Matthew Stevens beats Judd Trump after getting own cue back | date=2013-03-03 |work=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref> Trump qualified for the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Finals|PTC Finals]] by finishing second on the Order of Merit,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10 | title=Order of Merit 2012/2013 | website=snooker.org | accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref> but lost to [[Alfred Burden|Alfie Burden]] 3\u20134 in the first round.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-2293026/PTC-Grand-Finals-Judd-Trump-loses-Alfie-Burden-Galway.html | title=Trump dumped out by Burden in Galway as World No 1 suffers shock defeat | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=29 April 2013 | location=London | first=Mike | last=Dawes | date=14 March 2013}}</ref> He also lost in the first round of the [[2013 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] 3\u20135 to good friend [[Jack Lisowski]], surrendering his world number one ranking to Mark Selby in the process and headed into the [[2013 World Snooker Championship|2013 World Championship]] in less than auspicious form.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21940261 | title=China Open: John Higgins & Judd Trump out in first round | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 April 2013| date=26 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21988562 | title=Neil Robertson beats Mark Selby to win China Open title | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 April 2013| date=31 March 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTrump said that he had prepared better than ever for the World Championship and beat Dominic Dale in the first round for the second year in a row, this time by 10\u20135.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3155743,00.html | title=Trump In Shape For Title Tilt | website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |date=2013-04-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130427063035/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3155743,00.html |archive-date=2013-04-27 |url-status=dead}}</ref> At 8\u20137 ahead in the last 16 against [[Marco Fu]], Trump raced away with five consecutive frames to triumph 13\u20137 and set up a quarter-final clash with [[Shaun Murphy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3159650,00.html |title=Strong Finish Puts Trump Into Quarters |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |website=worldsnooker.com |date=27 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429233645/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~3159650%2C00.html |archivedate=29 April 2013 }}</ref> Trump came from 3\u20138 down to level at 8\u20138 at the conclusion of the second session. The deciding frame lasted 53 minutes with Trump winning it on the yellow to seal a 13\u201312 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump beats Murphy in Classic |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3164065,00.html |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |date=1 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504072937/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3164065,00.html |archive-date=2013-05-04 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He met [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the semi-finals, but was unable to capitalise on the chances that came his way: though he potted a ball in 24 of the 28 frames played, he could only make four breaks above 50 in an 11\u201317 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronnie O'Sullivan beats Judd Trump to reach World final |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/22400372 | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=2019-12-28 |date=2013-05-04 |first=Ben |last=Dirs}}</ref> Trump said afterwards \"It's probably the worst I've played all tournament. I would've probably expected to lose to anyone the way I played.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3167132,00.html | title=Rocket Blasts Into Fifth World Final |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] | date=2013-05-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507100037/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3167132,00.html |archive-date=2013-05-07 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013/2014 ===\n[[File:Judd Trump at Snooker German Masters (Martin Rulsch) 2014-02-01 18.jpg|thumb|2014 German Masters]]\nAt the start of the season Trump was ranked third in the [[Snooker world rankings 2013/2014|world rankings]]. He began the season poorly as he lost in the first round of the [[2013 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]], [[2013 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] and [[2013 International Championship|International Championship]], as well as failing to qualify for the [[2013 Indian Open|Indian Open]].<ref name=\"2013/14\">{{cite web|title=Judd Trump 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=12&season=2013|website=snooker.org|accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref> In November, he reached the final of the minor-ranking [[European Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 6|Kay Suzanne Memorial Cup]] but lost 1\u20134 to [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/EuropeanTour6Article/0,,13165~3532038,00.html | title=Results | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |website=worldsnooker.com |date=2013-11-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131122123554/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/EuropeanTour6Article/0,,13165~3532038,00.html |archive-date=2013-11-22 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nLater that month, he made the first official [[maximum break]] of his career in the [[European Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 7|Antwerp Open]] during a last-32 defeat against [[Mark Selby]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump Makes 147 In Antwerp |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3538266,00.html |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |date=15 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131129203943/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~3538266%2C00.html |archivedate=29 November 2013 }}</ref>\nHe reached the fourth round of the [[2013 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], where Allen defeated him 6\u20134, and he lost 5\u20136 to [[Marco Fu]] in the opening round of the [[2014 Masters (snooker)|Masters]].<ref name=\"2013/14\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/25715768 | title=Masters 2014: Judd Trump loses to Marco Fu in first round | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=22 January 2014| date=13 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2014 German Masters|German Masters]], he dropped just four frames in winning five matches to reach his first ranking final of the season where he played [[Ding Junhui]]. Trump was two frames ahead twice in the first session but ended it level at 4\u20134; he then lost five of the next six frames upon resumption of play to be defeated 5\u20139.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/26009924 | title=Ding Junhui in historic German Masters win over Judd Trump | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=6 May 2014| date=2 February 2014 }}</ref> At the [[2014 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], he was defeated 3\u20134 by [[John Higgins]] in the last 16.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12040/9188318/welsh-open-john-higgins-tops-judd-trump-ronnie-osullivan-awaits|title=Welsh Open: John Higgins tops Judd Trump; Ronnie O'Sullivan awaits|date=27 February 2014|accessdate=14 March 2014|work=[[Sky Sports]]}}</ref> Higgins was again the victor when the two met in the last 16 of the [[2014 World Open (snooker)|World Open]], winning 5\u20134 after Trump had taken a 4\u20130 lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/sport/story/291137.html|title=Higgins rallies to remarkable comeback against Trump|date=13 March 2014|accessdate=14 March 2014|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Trump won the non-ranking [[2014 Championship League|Championship League]] title during the season by beating [[Martin Gould]] 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3701471,00.html | title=Trump Triumphs At Championship League |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] | accessdate=6 May 2014| date=7 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nTrump defeated [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]] and [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] to reach the quarter-finals of the [[2014 World Snooker Championship|2014 World Championship]], where he played [[Neil Robertson]].<ref name=\"2013/14\"/> Trump led 6\u20132, 9\u20136, and 11\u20138, before Robertson launched a bold counterattack to take the last five frames and win the match 13\u201311.<ref>{{cite news|title=World Snooker Championship 2014: Robertson in semi-finals|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/27233268|work=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=30 April 2014|date=30 April 2014}}</ref> Trump received criticism for not acknowledging the fact that, during the match, Robertson had become the first player to make 100 centuries in a single season, instead choosing to walk out of the arena.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/Judd-Trump-World-Snooker-Championship-Neil/story-21042206-detail/story.html | title=Judd Trump out of World Snooker Championship as Neil Robertson racks up ton of tons | newspaper=[[Bath Chronicle]] |first=Chris |last=Bailey |date=2014-05-01 |accessdate=6 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507015227/http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/Judd-Trump-World-Snooker-Championship-Neil/story-21042206-detail/story.html | archive-date=7 May 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/27234957 | title=World Snooker Championship: Neil Robertson record played down | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=6 May 2014| date=2014-05-01 }}</ref> He later said that Robertson's achievement meant nothing to him and he chose to congratulate his opponent after the match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/sport/story/304023.html | title=Trump not impressed by Robertson record | publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] | accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014/2015 ===\nTrump was thrashed 0\u20135 by [[Stephen Maguire]] in the third round of the [[2014 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]], but responded a week later by claiming his fourth ranking title, and his first for 20 months, at the [[2014 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]],<ref name=\"2014/15\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=12 | title=Judd Trump 2014/2015 | website=snooker.org | accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> by defeating home favourite [[Neil Robertson]] 9\u20135 in the final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3965284,00.html | title=Trump wins Australian Goldfields Open |date=2014-07-06 |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] | accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> He reached the final of the [[European Tour 2014/2015 \u2013 Event 2|Paul Hunter Classic]] but lost 2\u20134 to [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Allen wins Paul Hunter Classic |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4096292,00.html|website=worldsnooker.com|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]|date=24 August 2014|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> He then suffered first and second round exits to [[Dominic Dale]] and [[Jamie Burnett]] respectively in the next two ranking events.<ref name=\"2014/15\"/> He advanced to the final of the [[2014 Champion of Champions|Champion of Champions]] but fell 3\u20138 down to [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]], before reducing his deficit to a single frame by taking four successive frames with the help of two centuries. However, O'Sullivan won the two frames he needed to triumph 10\u20137, with Trump claiming his opponent's standard of play throughout the match was the best he had ever encountered.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/sport/story/367021.html | title=O'Sullivan sees off Trump challenge to seal title | publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] | accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref> The pair also met in the final of the [[2014 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] in which Trump was 4\u20139 behind with a highest break of just 56. However, he won the 14th frame and then made back-to-back centuries and a break of 86 to only trail 8\u20139. He was 0\u201359 down in the next frame, but cleared the table with a 67 break to send the match into an unlikely decider; O'Sullivan then made a title-winning break after Trump had failed to escape from a snooker. O'Sullivan afterwards described the match as the hardest of his career.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/30369049 | title=Ronnie O'Sullivan beats Judd Trump to win UK Championship |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |date=2014-12-08 | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=2019-12-28}}</ref> At the [[2015 Masters (snooker)|Masters]], Trump lost 4\u20136 against Stephen Maguire in the first round.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/30780077 | title=Masters 2015: Stephen Maguire and Neil Robertson win 6\u20134 | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=2015-01-12 |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> He made the second 147 of his career in the quarter-finals of the [[2015 German Masters|German Masters]], but was knocked out 4\u20135 by [[Mark Selby]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/German-Masters-Judd-Trump-racks-second-career-147/story-25990306-detail/story.html | title=German Masters: Judd Trump racks up second career 147 in quarter-final defeat to Mark Selby | newspaper=[[Bath Chronicle]] |date=2015-02-07 |first=Luke |last=Baker |accessdate=3 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518104823/http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/German-Masters-Judd-Trump-racks-second-career-147/story-25990306-detail/story.html | archive-date=18 May 2015 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt the inaugural [[2015 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]], Trump eliminated [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 4\u20133 on the final black, but then fell 1\u20135 behind against [[Martin Gould]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/wales/31995869 | title=World Grand Prix: Judd Trump beats Mark Williams in Llandudno | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=2015-03-20 |accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref> However, he then took five successive frames, outscoring Gould by 395 points to 37, to win the match 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport/other-sport/watch-judd-trump-secures-place-8892973 | title=Judd Trump secures place in World Grand Prix final after remarkable comeback |date=2015-03-21 |first=Liam |last=Randall |newspaper=[[Daily Post (North Wales)|Daily Post]] | accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref> He played O'Sullivan for the third time in a final this season and was 4\u20137 behind, but then won six frames in a row, which included a 142 break (the highest of the tournament), to finish 10\u20137 and claim his second title of the season.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-3006987/Judd-Trump-beats-Ronnie-O-Sullivan-win-inaugural-Grand-Prix-title-Llandudno.html | title=Judd Trump beats Ronnie O'Sullivan to win inaugural Grand Prix title in Llandudno | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref> He also reached the semi-finals of the [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015 \u2013 Finals|PTC Grand Final]], where he lost 2\u20134 to Williams.<ref name=\"2014/15\"/>\n\nAt the [[2015 World Snooker Championship|2015 World Championship]], Trump produced his best snooker in the quarter-finals where he knocked in four centuries during a 13\u20134 thrashing of [[Ding Junhui]]. He stated afterwards that if he could play to the same standard in the rest of the event he would secure his first world title.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12040/9828092/ill-trump-blows-away-ding | title=Judd Trump crushes Ding Junhui 13\u20134 to reach World Championship semi-finals | date=2015-04-29 |work=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref> After holding an early 2\u20131 lead over [[Stuart Bingham]] in the semi-finals, Trump could not hold onto his advantage and fell 16\u201314 behind. He then made successive centuries to force a deciding frame in which he missed a red to the middle pocket due to a kick, and Bingham took the match 17\u201316.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/World-Snooker-Championship-Judd-Trump-says-semi/story-26434636-detail/story.html | title=World Snooker Championship: Judd Trump says semi-final defeat to Stuart Bingham was tough to take | newspaper=[[Bath Chronicle]] |date=2015-05-03 |first=Luke |last=Baker |accessdate=3 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723011517/http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/World-Snooker-Championship-Judd-Trump-says-semi/story-26434636-detail/story.html | archive-date=23 July 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== 2015/2016 ===\nIn the defence of his [[2015 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]] title, Trump was knocked out in the quarter-finals 1\u20135 by [[Stephen Maguire]].<ref name=\"2015/16\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=12 | title=Judd Trump 2015/2016 | website=snooker.org | accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> He reached the final of the [[2015 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], but a slow start from Trump saw him trail world number 54 [[Kyren Wilson]] 3\u20136 after the first session. Wilson also had leads of 8\u20134 and 9\u20137, before Trump sent the match into a deciding frame which Wilson won.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/34306578 | title=Shanghai Masters: Kyren Wilson pips Judd Trump to win first title | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=2015-09-20 |accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> Trump scored 278 points to nil in taking the first three frames of his third round [[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] match with [[Liang Wenbo]], but eventually lost 4\u20136. Trump branded the collapse an embarrassment and said it was the worst he had felt as a professional.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/34976937 | title=UK Championship: Judd Trump 'embarrassed' by collapse | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=2015-12-02 |first=Owen |last=Phillips |accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref> In the new year, Trump and [[Neil Robertson]] set a record of six centuries in a best-of-11-frame match (four from Trump and two from Robertson). Trump closed it out with a sublime 129 break to win 6\u20135, with Robertson describing it as \"the greatest Masters match ever\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/trump-wins-greatest-ever-masters-match/ | title=Trump Wins \"Greatest Ever Masters Match\" |date=2016-01-15 |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] | accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref> He was knocked out 4\u20136 in the semi-finals by [[Barry Hawkins]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-3402726/Barry-Hawkins-reaches-Masters-final-surprise-victory-Judd-Trump.html | title=Barry Hawkins reaches first Masters final with surprise victory over Judd Trump | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis first title of the season came at the [[2016 Championship League|Championship League]] where he defeated [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 3\u20132 in the final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/trump-in-a-league-of-his-own/ | title=Trump in a League of his Own | date=2016-03-03 |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] | accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref> Soon afterwards he won his fifth ranking title and first for almost two years by beating [[Ricky Walden]] 10\u20134 in the [[2016 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/trump-conquers-china-again/ | title=Trump Conquers China Again | date=2016-04-03 |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] | accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref> After trailing Liang Wenbo 3\u20137 in the first round of the [[2016 World Snooker Championship|2016 World Championship]], Trump tweeted that the drinks would be on him if he could turn it around. He duly did by winning 10\u20138 and put a few hundred pounds behind the local bar.<ref>{{cite news |last=Richards |first=Joshua |title=Trump battles to costly victory |work=Western Daily Press (Bristol, England) |page=48 |date=22 April 2016 |via=[[Newsbank]]. Retrieved 6 December 2019.}}</ref> Trump could not escape from a similar position against [[Ding Junhui]] in the second round and was beaten 10\u201313.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/36132489 | title=World Snooker Championship: Ding Junhui knocks out Judd Trump | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=2016-04-25 |first=Owen |last=Phillips |accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016/2017 ===\n[[File:Ion Tiriac and Judd Trump.jpg|thumb|Trump after winning the [[2016 European Masters]] in [[Bucharest, Romania|Bucharest]]]]\nTrump thrashed [[John Higgins]] 4\u20130 in the quarter-finals of the [[2016 European Masters]] and then overcame [[Mark Selby]] 6\u20132 to play [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the final. Trump was down 6\u20138, but took each of the remaining three frames to triumph 9\u20138 and win his sixth ranking title.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/37602320| title=Judd Trump beats Ronnie O'Sullivan in European Masters final| work=[[BBC Sport]]| date=2016-10-09 |accessdate=2019-12-28}}</ref> In his next event, the [[2016 English Open (snooker)|English Open]], he comfortably beat Higgins again in the quarter-finals, this time 5\u20131, and then defeated [[Barry Hawkins]] 6\u20132 to make it 14 wins in a row.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/english-open/2016-2017/judd-trump-to-face-liang-wenbo-in-english-open-final_sto5913250/story.shtml| title= Judd Trump to face Liang Wenbo in English Open final |date=2016-10-16 |work=[[Eurosport]] |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> However, he lost 6\u20139 to [[Liang Wenbo]] in the final after having missed a good chance to make it 7\u20137.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/liang-claims-maiden-ranking-title/| title= Liang Claims Maiden Ranking Title| date=2016-10-16 |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]| accessdate=2019-12-29}}</ref> Trump edged past [[Shaun Murphy]] 6\u20135 on the final black to reach the semi-finals of the [[2016 International Championship|International Championship]] where he was knocked out 4\u20139 by [[Ding Junhui]].<ref name=\"2016/17\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=12&season=2016| title=Judd Trump 2016/2017| website=snooker.org| accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> He had a surprise 2\u20136 defeat to [[Oliver Lines]] in the second round of the [[2016 UK Championship|UK Championship]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/38124447| title=UK Championship 2016: Oliver Lines stuns Judd Trump to join dad Peter in round three| work=[[BBC Sport]]| date=2016-11-27 |first=Owen |last=Phillips |accessdate=2019-12-28}}</ref> He was 5\u20131 up on Higgins in the semi-finals of the [[2016 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] as he made three centuries and a 99 break, but Higgins recovered to win 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/38351800| title=Scottish Open: John Higgins stuns Judd Trump to reach final| work=[[BBC Sport]]| date=2016-12-17 |accessdate=2019-12-28}}</ref> In an extremely high quality first round match at the [[2017 Masters (snooker)|Masters]], Trump made two centuries and [[Marco Fu]] three, followed by nine further breaks above 50 as Fu edged through 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/the-masters/2016-2017/marco-fu-edges-out-judd-trump-in-epic-as-neil-robertson-sets-up-ronnie-o-sullivan-clash_sto6017890/story.shtml| title=Marco Fu edges out Judd Trump in epic as Neil Robertson sets up Ronnie O'Sullivan clash |date=2017-01-17 |first=Desmond |last=Kane |work=[[Eurosport]] |accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHawkins missed a match-ball yellow in their quarter-final clash at the [[2017 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], and Trump cleared the colours to win the match 5\u20134. He then defeated [[Scott Donaldson]] 6\u20133 to play [[Stuart Bingham]] in the final;<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/39010074| title=Welsh Open 2017: Judd Trump beats Barry Hawkins in final frame to reach semi-final| work=[[BBC Sport]]| date=2017-02-17 |accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref> he was 0\u20134 down, before recovering to lead 8\u20137, but lost the last two frames and the match.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/39022490| title=Welsh Open 2017: Stuart Bingham beats Judd Trump 9\u20138 in final| work=[[BBC Sport]]| date=2017-02-19 |accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref> Another final followed at the [[2017 Gibraltar Open|Gibraltar Open]] as he come back from 0\u20132 down in the semi-finals against [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]], but he lost the final 2\u20134 to Murphy.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/murphy-rules-rock/| title=Murphy Rules the Rock| date=2017-03-05 |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]| accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref> He reached his third ranking event final inside a month at the [[2017 Players Championship (snooker)|Players Championship]] where he reeled off a match-defining six frames in a row from 2\u20135 down to Fu, and went on to win his seventh ranking title 10\u20138.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/wales/39242629| title=Players Championship: Judd Trump beats Marco Fu 10\u20138 final| work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2017-03-12 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> In the third round of the [[2017 China Open (snooker)|China Open]], Trump made his first televised 147 as he defeated [[Tian Pengfei]] 5\u20133,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/39447052|title=Judd Trump makes maximum 147 break in China Open last-16 victory|work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2017-03-30 |accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> but he suffered a surprise 3\u20135 loss to [[Hossein Vafaei]] in the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"2016/17\"/>\n\nTrump went into the [[2017 World Snooker Championship|2017 World Championship]] declaring: \"I honestly believe I can play to a standard which is very rare nowadays,\" and that he was \"the best\" in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Championship 2017: Favourite tag is an 'advantage' \u2013 Judd Trump|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/39602348|work=BBC Sport|first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |date=2017-04-14 |accessdate=19 April 2017}}</ref> He won the first four frames in his opening match, before [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]] responded to lead 5\u20134. Trump appeared to be struggling with a shoulder injury and eventually lost the match 8\u201310 to a player ranked 52 places below him in the rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/world-championship/2016-2017/1000-1-outsider-rory-mcleod-stuns-judd-trump-in-huge-crucible-upset_sto6135792/story.shtml|title=1,000-1 outsider Rory McLeod stuns Judd Trump in huge Crucible upset |date=2017-04-19 |first=Desmond |last=Kane |work=[[Eurosport]] |accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/trump-suffers-shock-defeat-mcleod/|title=Trump Suffers Shock Defeat by McLeod |date=2017-04-19 |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017/2018 ===\n\nTrump was third in the [[Snooker world rankings 2017/2018|world rankings]] at the start of the season. He successfully defended his [[2017 European Masters (snooker)|European Masters]] title in October, defeating [[Stuart Bingham]] 9\u20137 in the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/41547011|title=Judd Trump beats Stuart Bingham 9\u20137 to retain European Masters title|date=8 October 2017|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=7 May 2019}}</ref> The following month, he reached the quarter-finals of the [[2017 International Championship (snooker)|International Championship]] where he was edged out 5\u20136 by [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]]. He then reached the final of the [[2017 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] for the second time, but was heavily defeated 3\u201310 by [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/osullivan-wins-30th-ranking-title/|title=O'Sullivan wins 30th ranking title|date=18 November 2017 |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |access-date=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe made semi-final appearances at three other ranking events this season: at the [[2017 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]], he lost 4\u20136 to [[Cao Yupeng]] whom he had defeated two months earlier in the semi-finals of the European Masters; at the [[2018 German Masters|German Masters]], he was beaten 1\u20136 by [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]], after making the highest break of the tournament (140) in his quarter-final clash with [[Ding Junhui]]; and in defending his title at the [[2018 Players Championship (snooker)|Players Championship]], he was narrowly defeated by Ronnie O'Sullivan 5\u20136. In January, he reached the semi-finals of the [[2018 Masters (snooker)|2018 Masters]] where, despite leads of 3\u20131 and 5\u20132 earlier in the match, he was eliminated 5\u20136 by [[Kyren Wilson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/42761209|title=Masters 2018: Kyren Wilson edges Judd Trump 6\u20135 to reach first final|date=20 January 2018|first=Saj|last=Chowdhury|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2018 World Snooker Championship|2018 World Championship]], Trump came close to suffering a first round defeat by Crucible debutant [[Chris Wakelin]] who took the match to a deciding frame.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Snooker Championship 2018: Judd Trump beats debutant Chris Wakelin |last=Phillips |first=Owen |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=27 April 2018 |accessdate=2 October 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/43975971 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429153350/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/43907426 |archivedate=9 May 2018 }}</ref> After beating [[Ricky Walden]] 13\u20139 in the second round, he was narrowly defeated in the quarter-finals by John Higgins in another final frame decider, the first time they had met in a World Championship match since the 2011 final.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Snooker Championship 2018: John Higgins wins epic against Judd Trump to complete semis line-up |last=Phillips |first=Owen |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2 May 2018 |accessdate=2 October 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/43975971 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503004442/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/43975971 |archivedate=3 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n=== 2018/2019 ===\nTrump began the [[Snooker season 2018/2019|2018/2019 season]] fifth in the [[Snooker world rankings 2018/2019|world rankings]]. His defence of the [[2018 European Masters|European Masters]] ended with a surprise 2\u20134 defeat against [[Tian Pengfei]] in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2018/1003/1000802-pengfei-knocks-trump-out-of-european-masters/|title=Pengfei knocks Trump out of European Masters|date=3 October 2018|publisher=[[RTE]]|access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref> He won his first ranking title of the season at the [[2018 Northern Ireland Open|Northern Ireland Open]], beating [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 9\u20137 in the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/46254769|title=Northern Ireland Open: Judd Trump beats Ronnie O'Sullivan 9\u20137 in final|date=18 November 2018|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref> At the [[2018 UK Championship|UK Championship]], he suffered a 4\u20136 fourth round loss to [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]]. He then reached the semi-final of the [[2018 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]], but was defeated 3\u20136 by [[Shaun Murphy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://asia.eurosport.com/snooker/scottish-open/2018-2019/snooker-news-shaun-murphy-holds-off-judd-trump-to-meet-mark-allen-in-scottish-open-final_sto7053721/story.shtml |title=Shaun Murphy holds off Judd Trump, to meet Mark Allen in Scottish Open final |date=16 December 2018 |work=[[Eurosport]] |location=Asia |access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> In January, Trump won his first [[Masters (snooker)|Masters]] title, beating [[Kyren Wilson]], [[Mark Selby]] and [[Neil Robertson]] en route to the final, where his opponent was Ronnie O'Sullivan. Trump dominated the match, taking a 7\u20131 lead, and eventually won it 10\u20134.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/46940199|title=Judd Trump beats Ronnie O'Sullivan to win Masters final 10\u20134 at Alexandra Palace|date=20 January 2019|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref> A month later, he won his second ranking event of the season, the [[2019 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]], beating [[Ali Carter]] 10\u20136 in the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/47193115|title=World Grand Prix: Judd Trump beats Ali Carter 10\u20136 to win World Grand Prix|date=11 February 2019|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo more semi-final appearances in March 2019, at the [[2019 Players Championship (snooker)|Players Championship]] and the [[2019 Tour Championship|Tour Championship]], were followed by the biggest success of Trump's career so far, when he won the [[2019 World Snooker Championship|2019 World Championship]]. He defeated [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh]] 10\u20139 in the first round, having trailed 3\u20136 after the first session.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/48039317|title=World Championship 2019: Judd Trump overturns 6\u20133 deficit to beat Thepchaiya Un-Nooh|date=24 April 2019|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref> In the second round against [[Ding Junhui]], he led 5\u20131 and trailed 7\u20139, then won six consecutive frames to clinch a 13\u20139 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/48097983|title=World Championship 2019: Judd Trump beats Ding Junhui to reach quarter-finals|date=29 April 2019|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref> A comfortable 13\u20136 quarter-final win over [[Stephen Maguire]] took him to the semi-finals, where he beat [[Gary Wilson (snooker player)|Gary Wilson]] 17\u201311 to secure his second appearance in a world final.\n\nHis opponent was [[John Higgins]], in a re-run of the 2011 final. Trailing 4\u20135 in the early stages, Trump dominated the second session, winning eight consecutive frames to lead 12\u20135 overnight, a display which [[Steve Davis]] described as the \"controlled annihilation of a great player\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/48170912|title=World Championship 2019: Judd Trump leads John Higgins 12\u20135 in Crucible final|date=5 May 2019|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref> Trump led 16\u20139 going into the final session, and won the opening two frames of the evening to seal an 18\u20139 win, and with it his first world title. The two players scored eleven centuries between them, a record for a professional match. Trump's seven centuries in the final equalled Ding Junhui's record for the most by one player in a World Championship match.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/48178462|title=World Championship 2019: Judd Trump beats John Higgins 18\u20139 in Crucible final|date=6 May 2019|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref> Winning the world title also made Trump the 11th player to complete snooker's [[Triple Crown (snooker)|Triple Crown]].\n\n=== 2019/2020 ===\nTrump's first appearance as reigning [[List of world snooker champions|world champion]] was at the [[2019 International Championship|International Championship]] in August 2019. He won the tournament by defeating [[Shaun Murphy]] 10\u20133 in the final,<ref name=2019IntChamp>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/international-championship/2019-2020/snooker-news-judd-trump-demolishes-shaun-murphy-to-win-international-championship_sto7404467/story.shtml |title=Trump demolishes Murphy to win International Championship |date=2019-08-11 |first=Alexander |last=Netherton |work=Eurosport |access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> regaining the number one position in the snooker world rankings ahead of [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref name=2019IntChamp /> He also won the [[2019 World Open (snooker)|World Open]] early in the season, defeating [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh]] 10\u20135 in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/50282836 |title=Judd Trump beats Thepchaiya Un-Nooh in World Open final |date=2019-11-03 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nHe reached the final of the [[2019 Champion of Champions|Champion of Champions]], where his opponent was [[Neil Robertson]]. Leading 9\u20138 in a best-of-19 frames match, Trump appeared to be on the verge of claiming the title as Robertson required snookers to win the 18th frame. However, Trump was eventually defeated 10\u20139.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/champion-of-champions/2019-2020/snooker-news-neil-robertson-beats-judd-trump-in-thrilling-champion-of-champions-final_sto7533646/story.shtml |title=Emotional Robertson beats Trump in thrilling Champion of Champions final |date=2019-11-10 |first=James |last=Gray |work=Eurosport |access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn November, Trump won his third ranking tournament of the season, the [[2019 Northern Ireland Open|Northern Ireland Open]]. In the final, he beat Ronnie O'Sullivan 9\u20137, the same scoreline with which he had won the title the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/trump-beats-rocket-in-epic-final/174172 |title=Northern Ireland Open: Judd Trump beats Ronnie O'Sullivan 9\u20137 in thrilling final |date=2019-11-17 |work=Sporting Life |agency=Press Association |access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> He failed to earn a place in the [[2020 European Masters|European Masters]] the following month, losing 3\u20135 to [[Ian Burns (snooker player)|Ian Burns]] in the first qualifying round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://snookerhq.com/2019/12/19/seeds-troubled-in-european-masters-qualifying/ |title=Seeds Troubled in European Masters Qualifying |first=David |last=Caulfield |date=2019-12-19 |website=SnookerHQ |access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> He defeated Neil Robertson 9\u20136 in the final of the [[2020 German Masters|German Masters]], a match that featured a lot of \"high-class safety\", to claim his fourth ranking title of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/51351874 |title=German Masters: World champion Judd Trump beats Neil Robertson in final |date=2020-02-02 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March 2020, Trump claimed a record-equalling fifth ranking title of the season when he defeated [[Yan Bingtao]] 10\u20134 in the final of the [[2020 Players Championship (snooker)|Players Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2020/0301/1119583-players-championship-judd-trump/ |title=Trump claims Players Championship in style |date=2020-03-01 |website=[[RT\u00c9.ie]] |access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> With this victory, he became the fifth player to win five ranking events in a single season, after [[Stephen Hendry]], [[Ding Junhui]], [[Mark Selby]] and Ronnie O'Sullivan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/51700279 |title=Trump beats Yan Bingtao to win Players Championship |date=2020-03-01 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nTwo weeks later, on 15 March, he claimed the all-time record of six ranking titles in a single season, defeating [[Kyren Wilson]] 4\u20133 at an empty venue at the [[Gibraltar Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/judd-trump-first-player-ever-six-ranking-titles-season-gibraltar-open-win-12402379/ |title=Judd Trump is first player ever to six ranking titles in a season with Gibraltar Open win |date=2020-03-15 |work=Metro.co.uk |access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n== Performance and rankings timeline ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournaments'''\n! [[Snooker season 2005/2006|2005/<br/>06]]\n! [[Snooker season 2006/2007|2006/<br/>07]]\n! [[Snooker season 2007/2008|2007/<br/>08]]\n! [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/<br/>09]]\n! [[Snooker season 2009/2010|2009/<br/>10]]\n! [[Snooker season 2010/2011|2010/<br/>11]]\n! [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/<br/>12]]\n! [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/<br/>13]]\n! [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/<br/>14]]\n! [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/<br/>15]]\n! [[Snooker season 2015/2016|2015/<br/>16]]\n! [[Snooker season 2016/2017|2016/<br/>17]]\n! [[Snooker season 2017/2018|2017/<br/>18]]\n! [[Snooker season 2018/2019|2018/<br/>19]]\n! [[2019\u201320 snooker season|2019/<br/>20]]\n! [[Snooker season 2020/2021|2020/<br/>21]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Rankings]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|website=snooker.org|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">From the 2010/2011 season it shows the ranking at the beginning of the season.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref group=\"nb\">New players on the Main Tour do not have a ranking.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2006/2007|71]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2007/2008|51]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2008/2009|41]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2009/2010|30]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2010/2011|27]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2011/2012|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2012/2013|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2013/2014|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2014/2015|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2015/2016|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2016/2017|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2017/2018|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2018/2019|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2019/2020|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Snooker world rankings 2020/2021|1]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"20\"| '''Ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| [[Riga Masters (snooker)|Riga Masters]]<ref group=\"nb\">The event was called the Riga Open (2014/2015\u20132015/2016)</ref>\n| colspan=\"9\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Tournament Not Held\n|  colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Minor-Rank.\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2016 Riga Masters|QF]]\n|style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" | A\n|style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" | A\n|style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" | A\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| {{nowrap|[[International Championship]]}}\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Tournament Not Held\n|  style=